```

### Path of the Blood Seeker
Red. In the heat of battle, the color red is sometimes your world. As more and more death occurs around you, you remember less and less of the time; but you always remember red.  The blood on you that you awaken to fills you with a zealous feeling. It is indescribable, yet comforting. This is the feeling you chase when you go into battle. The exhilaration is worth death, especially the death of someone who would stand in your way.

#### Bloodshed
Beginning at 3rd level, your attacks and vitality increase in brutality as you smell and feel blood. While raging and not wearing Medium or Heavy armor, you gain a point of bloodshed up to your Constitution modifier (minimum of 1) whenever you reduce an enemy to 0 it points, score a critical hit, or are reduced to half health (can only occur once every hour). You gain +1 to your AC per stack of bloodshed up to a maximum of +3. When your rage ends, you lose all stacks of Bloodshed.
	While raging, after you roll damage for a successful melee attack roll, you can spend a point of Bloodshed to reroll any amount of the die you rolled for the attack. If any of the new rolls are the maximum amount of damage for that die, you add your Constitution modifier to the total damage per instance of maximum amount rolled.

#### Consumption
Starting at 6th level, your enemies pain becomes your sustenance.

After you successfully hit with a melee attack roll, you can spend a point of bloodshed before rolling damage to heal for the amount of damage done with that attack. If this attack kills the creature, you gain additional hit points equal to your Constitution modifier + Barbarian level.

#### Bloodthirsty
Starting at 10th level, Your adrenaline from pain and anger gives you a second burst of strength at the cost of your foes.

If you are reduced to half your maximum hit point total, you get a free use of Consumption on your next turn without using a point of Bloodshed. If you do not use this free use of Consumption by the end of your next turn, it is lost.


Additionally, you gain the following feature while under half of your maximum hit point total. If you heal to above half of your hit point maximum, you lose these features. You can only gain these features once per Encounter.

If you spend a point of Bloodshed, gain the following attribute until the end of your turn.

* Gain 1d8 bonus damage of the damage type that was used in the attack.
* Your critical hit threshold is increased to 19-20.
* If you reduce a creature to 0 hit points while an ally is within 5 feet of you and the creature, you and your ally gain 1d6 temporary hit points.

<div class='pageNumber'>3</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 3 | BARBARIAN</div>
\page

#### Bloodbath
Starting at 14th level, you have eyes only for seeking more blood, with no regard for it's owner. 

Whenever you spend a point of Bloodshed while benefiting from Bloodthirsty, as a bonus action, you move up to 40 feet (regardless of current remaining movement speed) and must use the movement to go towards the closest creature to you, even allies. You do not provoke attacks of opportunity for this movement. As you come into range of a creature to make an attack roll, do so with advantage and then move on to the next closest creature that you have yet to attack with any remaining movement. If multiple targets are the same distance away, choose randomly on who to attack. If any of these attacks kill a creature, you gain another 15 feet of movement and a +1 to all future attack rolls for this usage of the ability to a maximum of +5.
You cannot use this ability if your speed is currently 0. This ability can only be used once per rage.


&nbsp;

### Earth Shaker

Legends all over the world have their own reasons for how the mountains were made. Dwarves carving out the land, Gods summoning plateaus for their temples, myths abound with the storytelling awe and wonder for a child. But for a select few of extraordinary power, the ground truly does bend for them. With the rage and strength rumored to belong to the gods, the land beneath their feet heads their will.

#### Tremor Strength
Beginning at 3rd level, your attacks echo out a small tremor from your blows.

As a bonus action, you can add this affect to your next attack roll. All creatures within 5 feet of your target must make a Constitution saving throw equal to 10 + Rage Damage or have their speed reduced by 5 feet and suffer a -1 to any attack rolls made until the end of your next turn. On a save, nothing happens. Once a creature makes this save, they are immune to further effects of this effect for 1 hour.

While raging, your Strength score increases by 1, and can exceed the normal limit of 20. This increases to a bonus of 2 at 12th level.

#### Grounded Impact
Starting at 6th level, you can double down on your own defense while throwing away foes nearby.

As an action, you can perform a Strength check (DC 14 - your Strength modifier) . On a success, You slam the ground and knock up large chunks of debris at all creatures within 5 feet as it scatters around you. All creatures within the area must succeed on a Dexterity saving throw or take 2d6+1 bludgeoning damage, are moved 5 feet away from you and knocked prone. On a success, they take half damage, are moved 5 feet away from you, but are not knocked prone.

The surrounding affected area is now difficult terrain for all creatures except you, and provides half cover for any creature in the center of the area.

You can perform this move once per rage.
If you throw a chunk of debris created by this ability as an improvised ranged attack, you have proficiency for the attack and it deals 1d6 + Strength modifier for damage.

```
```

#### Body of the Earth
Starting at 10th level, your body gains a rocklike quality while raging.

You gain the feature, Immutable Form: You are immune to any spell or effect that would alter your form. Additionally, you become immune to petrification.
If you use Grounded Impact, your AC increases by 1 until the end of your next turn.

#### Mountain’s Rage
Starting at 14th level, the mountains call and sing for you and your fury.

As an action, you can perform a Strength check  (DC 17 - Strength modifier) to punch stone, dirt, or sand beneath you. On a success, you punch into the ground below you and summon a 30 foot tall, 15’ square pillar of earth beneath a point you can see within 30 feet. All creatures within the area must make a Dexterity saving throw (DC 12 + Rage Damage) or they are struck by the pillar and take 2d12 bludgeoning damage. If the pillar collides with a ceiling, the creature takes an additional 2d6 bludgeoning damage and is restrained. A restrained creature can reattempt it’s Dexterity saving throw at the start of each of its turns to end their restrained condition. If the creature's speed is reduced in any way when it is targeted by this ability, they have disadvantage on their saving throw to avoide the pillar. On a save, the creature move to the nearest unoccupied location.

Because you created this pillar, you know it’s weak point, and can perform a melee attack on it to make it crumble into a 15’ tall pile of rubble that provides 3/4's cover and acts as difficult terrain.


<div class='pageNumber'>4</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 4 | BARBARIAN</div>
\page
## Bard
So many tradesman stick to the safe and tried paths of talents and knowledge. Seeking stories and wooeing crowds with their charm and looks, the line between a bard and a conman is becoming more blurred with the passing of time. But some seek to earn their titles with the grandest of peformances, or the most honest of jests. To these practitioners of the arts, the stage is where the heart can come alive.

### Circus Performer
Raised in troupes and by carnies and minstrels, you embellish in the art of performing. The stories of plays, and tales from song light the fire behind your eyes hotter than fire you perform with. Through the years you have gained many talents and tricks, shadowing performers as they came and went with shows. Now you embark to create your own tricks, your own name, and maybe one day have people know you by your show.

#### Animal Performers
Starting at 3rd level, you become proficient in Performance and Animal Handling. You also gain the ability to summon 1 animal for your acts at a given time, or for your personal protection as if casting Conjure Animals but ignoring the challenge rating limit and how many are summoned. As an action, you can use a Bardic Inspiration point to summon one of the listed animals from a portal you create to an unoccupied space within 5 feet of you. Summoned creatures have their own initiative and obey all verbal commands you issue. If you give no commands, the creature will protect itself to the best of its ability. Your summoned animal starts with a Bardic Inspiration die. As you gain more levels in Bard, you can summon more exotic animals, provided you have the performance skill to handle them. If the summoned animal hits 0 hit points, it is instantly sucked back into a portal that opens underneath it and cannot be re-summoned for 24 hours. You can dismiss a summoned animal with an action back into a portal.



#### Animal Performers
| Bard Level | Min. Performance skill bonus | Summoned Animal |
|-------|---------|-----------|
|3rd|6|Flying Monkey or Dolphin|
|6th|9|Black Bear or Sea Lion|
|10th|12|Brown Bear or Shark|
|14th|15|Tiger or Giant Octopus|
|18th|16|Elephant or Killer Whale|

#### Crack of the Whip
Starting at 3rd level, you become proficient with Whips, and any damage made by a whip you wield counts as magical damage.

You can use the Fighter’s Disarming Attack maneuver with a whip by using a Bardic Inspiration die instead of a Superiority die. The Strength save for this maneuver is (DC 10 + your Dexterity modifier + your proficiency bonus), and upon a success you can choose to force the target to drop the item at their feet or you can pull it back to you and it drops at your feet. 

Additionally, If you have an Animal Performer out, you can use a bonus action to crack the whip and grant the Animal Performer a free attack on your turn with advantage, and 10 feet of additional movement speed on their next turn.

#### Ringmaster
Starting at 6th level, As an action you can use a bardic inspiration die to summon a ring with burning edges 5 feet in front of you. The ring is 10 ft in diameter and can be moved up to 30 feet as a bonus action. 

Creatures who come into contact with the ring must make a Dexterity saving throw against your spell save DC. On a fail, they take 2d6 + your Charisma modifier fire damage and are forced within the ring which then closes around them and causes them to be restrained. On a save, the target takes half damage but are not captured by the ring. Creatures restrained by the ring can attempt another saving throw on their subsequent turns. Ending a turn while still restrained by the ring causes 1d6 fire damage. If your Animal Summon is within range to make an attack on the creature when it first becomes restrained, it can make a free attack roll against it. The flames from the ring shed light in a 10 foot radius, and dim light another 10 feet past that, and can set loose items around it on fire.

This ability recharges on a long rest. At level 10 you gain 2 uses of this ability between long rests.

#### The Bells and Whistles
Starting at 14th level, you can use a bardic inspiration die to create one of the greatest shows on this plane to dazzle your audience with lights and illusions. You create an illusory circus tent 30 feet high with a  20 foot radius centered on you.

While in this area, you gain the following features
* A bonus to your Performance checks equal to your Bard level
* You and your Animal summon gain a +1 bonus to attack rolls, ability checks, and saving throws per non-ally creature up to a maximum of 5.
* You are immune to being Feared or Charmed.

Select a number of creatures within this area at the time of its creation up to half of your Bard level, and they must succeed on a Wisdom saving throw. On a fail, they all become Charmed to you, or they are blinded (your choice). They can attempt the save again at the end of any of their subsequent turns or after they take damage. If a charmed or blinded creature leaves the circus tent area, they are no longer charmed or blinded. On a success, the creature is unaffected by the illusion. Whether a targeted creature succeeds or fails the save, they cannot attack you or your Animal Summon until the start of your next turn.

You can use this feature once per long rest.


<div class='pageNumber'>5</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 1 | BARD</div>
\page

### College of the Jester


#### Joking way of life
Starting at 3rd level, through elation and laughter, you face every situation with a smile. Even in danger you evade and escape with style and wit. Whenever you are forced to make a Dexterity saving throw, you can instead use your Performance skill for the saving throw.

You also gain proficiency in a Musical Instrument and the ability to cast the Vicious Mockery cantrip. Vicious Mockery does not count against the number of known cantrips or spells for you.

#### Knee Slapper
Also at 3rd level, creating laughter truly is the best medicine, and you are able to share this medicine with those closest to you. Whenever a creature uses your Bardic Inspiration die, they gain temporary hit points for the amount they rolled on the Bardic Inspiration die and 1d4 hit points.
Additionally, if a creature rolls a natural 1-3 on an attack roll against you or an ally while they have a Bardic Inspiration die, they automatically fail their attack roll.
This threshold increases to 1-4 at 10th level.

#### Inspirational Mockery
At 6th level, the misfortune of life grants insatiable joy, and you can pocket these moments of mishap as material for a crippling delivery.

Whenever any creature automatically fails an attack roll made against a hostile creature, you gain a point of Inspirational Mockery, up to 3. As a bonus action, you can target a creature you can see and mentally fill their mind with a charmed image of the mistake you witnessed earlier. The creature must make a Wisdom saving throw against the image. On a fail, they disarm themselves of any held items, and drop prone, laughing to themselves over the experience until the end of their next turn or until they next take damage. On a successful save, the creature is unmoved by the image, and knows you tried to charm it. If the creature has 6 or less intelligence, they automatically succeed on their save.
Alternatively, you can spend a point of Inspirational Mockery as a free action to heal yourself for 1d6 health points per point spent. Inspirational Mockery points last for 5 minutes and then are removed.

#### Wait for it...

At 14th level, If you spend a Bardic Inspiration point, you can cast Vicious Mockery on up to 3 targets of your choice within 30 feet that you can see. If a creature is suffering from Inspirational Mockery, the damage dice for Vicious Mockery is increased to d6's. This particular ability is less powerful the more times a creature is subjected to it, decreasing the damage of Vicious Mockery by 1d4 per additional time it is used with this feature to a minimum of 1d4.

If a creature dies from one of these castings of Vicious Mockery, illusionary confetti appears and falls around them alongside a short celebratory horn sound, forcing hostile creatures that can see the phenomenon to make a Wisdom saving throw or be feared by you.

You can use this ability 3 times, but need 1 round between uses to rest your voice. All uses of this ability recharge on a long rest.


### College of the Musician

#### Serenade
Starting at 3rd level, you gain proficiency in 2 Musical Instruments and the ability to cast the spell Dissonant Whisper. This does not count against the number of known spells for you.
If you are wielding an instrument, you can use 1 hour practicing with it to attune yourself to it and have it count as a magical implement for your spellcasting. Spells that cause psychic or thunder damage have advantage on attack rolls, or cause disadvantage for saving throws to a number of creatures equal to your proficiency bonus if cast using an attuned instrument. At 10th level, this ability extends to spells that cause the charmed effect on a creature.

#### Stage Show
Also at 3rd level, you can use your action to create a performance full of emotions. Choose a number of creatures you can see within 30 feet up to your skill bonus to Performance to be affected by your show. Unwilling creatures must succeed on a Wisdom saving throw to resist the effects of your show. Choose 1 song to perform

&nbsp;


**The Hero’s Epic:** All affected creatures gain +1 to attack rolls and saving throws. The bonus to attack rolls is increased to +2 at 10th level.

&nbsp;


**The Stranger’s Lament:** All affected creatures suffer a -2 penalty to Constitution, Wisdom and Dexterity ability checks and saving throws.

&nbsp;


**Whimsey of the Heart:** All affected creatures are charmed to you. Creatures who save against your song know you tried to charm them.

&nbsp;


**Sorrow of the Soul:** All affected creatures suffer a -1 to all attack rolls and saving throws. The reduction to attack rolls is increased to -2 at 10th level.

&nbsp;


You must use a bonus action to maintain the Stage Show on each subsequent turn. If you are damaged while performing a Stage Show, you must succeed on a spell constitution save, or stop playing. If you stop your performance, you must wait 10 minutes before you can do another Stage Show. If a creature is unable to hear your performance, they cannot be affected by them. An unwilling creature who succeeds on their Wisdom saving throw to a song cannot be affected by another performance for 24 hours.

#### Soul Soothing Music
At 6th level, Your voice and instruments can strike divine chords. If you start a Stage Show performance on the same turn you give a creature a Bardic Inspiration die, that creature regains hit points equal to twice your Bard level.


<div class='pageNumber'>6</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 2 | BARD</div>
\page

#### Backup Band
At 14th level, you can summon a backup, spectral instrument as a bonus action to support your performances. Choose one of the following instruments and gain the associated bonus whenever you cast a spell that causes psychic or thunder damage, or whenever you perform a Stage Show.

&nbsp;

**Flute:**
Add an effect to slide 1 creature harmed by a spell you cast 10 ft in a direction of your choice. If performing a Stage Show, grant the affected creatures 5 ft of bonus movement until the start of your next turn.


**Drum:**
Add 10 feet to the range or area for a spell. If performing a stage show, impose disadvantage on any attack rolls performed by a creature targeted by stage show within 10 feet of you.


**Lute:**
Grant an ally you can see advantage on their next saving throw until the start of your next turn. If performing a stage show, Add a +1 to the saving throw requirement made by unwilling creatures. 


**Harp:**
Immediately after a relevant spell is cast and resolved, gain one free use of a 3rd level Sleep spell cast within the next minute. This can only occur once per long rest. If performing a Stage Show, all affected creatures gain 1d10 temporary hit points once per long rest.


**Bagpipes:**
Draws the attention of all creatures affected by a spell, causing them to use all of their movement to advance towards you on their next turn. If performing a Stage Show, you can choose 1 creature within 10 feet of you at the time of performing to succeed on a Constitution saving throw or become incapacitated. This can only occur once per Stage Show.

&nbsp;

Summoned instruments last for 1 minute, or can be dismissed with a bonus action.

#### Performer
Upon reaching 14th level, your courage on the stage bleeds through to other aspects of your life. You can now add your Dexterity ability modifier to all Charisma skill checks, and to the damage of any Bard spells. Additionally, any creature who tries to succeed on a saving throw to see through an illusion created by you has disadvantage.

&nbsp;

<div class='pageNumber'>6</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 3 | BARD</div>
\page
## Cleric
Many a person of faith follows a path marked as a righteous life by their deities. The preservation of life, nature, even things as specific as storms; all are noble pursuits, truly, but they are all smaller slices of the larger picture that governs the world. To the few enlightened enough, and privileged enough to be selected by the higher powers that govern the laws of physics and nature, a responsibility to maintain the cycle of life is entrusted the power to wield their forces.


### Time Domain
The Gods of Time - Kronos, Istus, Amaunator, Grumbar, Labelas Enoreth - uphold the most powerful and ancient law in the multiverse: Time. The Gods of time promote vitality and health but also the natural aging process of all mortals, the passing of time, day, night, and even the seasons. Time is the only true constant in a world filled with chaos, and even though some people fear this being altered in any way, there are others that seek to alter the limitations of the multiverse itself.


#### Time Domain Spells
| Cleric Level | Spells |
|-------|---------|
|1st|Expeditious Retreat, Sleep|
|3rd|Mirror Image, Misty Step|
|5th|Haste, Slow|
|7th|Banishment, Dimension Door|
|9th|Hold Monster, Wall of Force|

#### Bonus Cantrip
At 1st level, you learn a new cantrip called Temporal Pulse. They work as Cleric cantrips for you and don’t count against the number of cantrips in the Cleric Table.

#### Temporal Pulse
*enchantment Cantrip*
___
- **Casting Time:** 1 action
- **Range:** 15 foot cone
- **Components:** S, V
- **Duration:** Instantaneous

You launch a pulsing shock waves at a target that disrupts their bodily functions. Make a ranged spell attack on each creature in range. On a hit, the target takes 1d6 Thunder damage, and its speed is reduced by 10 feet until the start of our next turn.

The damage increases to 2d6 when you reach 5th level, 3d6 at 11th level, and 4d6 at 17th level.

```
```

### Timelines
Starting at 1st level, you can use your magic to slightly turn back time to give you more time to prepare yourself for something that endangers you. Whenever you fail a Dexterity saving throw, you can use your reaction to turn back time and reroll the saving throw and add half of your Cleric level to the result (minimum of 1). You can use this feature a number of times equal to your Wisdom modifier (a minimum of 1). You regain all expended uses when you finish a long rest

### Channel Divinity: Spell Paradox
At 2nd level, you can use your Channel Divinity to create a time paradox within your spells. Whenever you cast a spell that targets a single creature and doesn’t have a range of self, you can target a second creature in range with the same spell immediatly.

### Stretch Time
At 6th level, whenever you cast a Cleric spell of 1st level or higher with a duration of at least 1 minute, you can double its duration up to a maximum of 24 hours.

You can also use your bonus action to take the Dash action.

### Secular Spellcasting
Starting at 8th level, you add your Wisdom Modifier to the damage you deal with a Cleric Cantrip. Additionally, any effects from spells that reduce a creatures movement speed now has a 50% chance to reduce the target’s speed to 0.

### Across Time and Space
At 17th level, you have mastered time to your will and gain the following features:

&nbsp;


**Time Stop:** Time Stop is now a domain Spell for you. Like other domain spells, it is always prepared and counts as a Cleric spell for you.

&nbsp;


**Timeless:** You experience no further physical effects from aging. You cannot be aged magically and your natural lifespan is increased by five times.

&nbsp;


**Deja Vu:** You may re-cast one spell of 5th level or lower that you used previously on the same day without using a spell slot. You may only use this feature once per long rest.

&nbsp;


**Omen:** Whenever you would be damaged by an attack you can see coming, you warn your past self to try and change the present. Roll 1d4 and take the listed benefit:
1. You reacted too slow and were unsuccessful in changing anything
2. Reduce the primary damage received by 1d6
3. Increase your AC by 2 for the attack, or gain a +2 to your saving throw, whichever applies.
4. Force a reroll for the attack, or reroll your saving throw. The new roll must be used.

You can use this feature 2 times per long rest.

<div class='pageNumber'>7</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 1 | CLERIC</div>
\page

### Fate Domain

The Gods of Fate - Aesir, Bes, Hermod, Savras, and Tyche, all share dominion over the flow of fate, fortune, and destiny. It is the power of belief to which all things will be as they should, and that those who follow in their name shall receive what they were meant to. Being in the good graces of such entities can turn your life around, and give you an edge in life. Perhaps an incoming storm dies down in the nick of time, or an opponent's foot finds an unfortunate rock to trip up their stance and give you the edge. It would be foolish to not pay such divine beings homage.

#### Fate Domain Spells
| Cleric Level | Spells |
|-------|---------|
|1st|Shield of Faith, Divine Favor|
|3rd|Find Traps, Knock|
|5th|Clairvoyance, Counterspell|
|7th|Divination, Guardian of Faith|
|9th|Geas, Telekinesis|


#### Bonus Cantrip
At 1st level, you learn the True Strike cantrip. This works as a Cleric cantrip for you and doesn’t count against the number of cantrips you know from the Cleric Table.

#### Fortunate One
Also at 1st level, you fall into all sorts of luck just when you need it. When you are subjected to an effect that forces you to make a Dexterity saving throw to take only half damage, you can use your Wisdom (Religion) skill for the roll instead.

#### Channel Divinity: Lucky Hit
At 2nd level, you can use your Channel Divinity as a bonus action to create the best possible setup for your attacks, though you still need to execute them. Until the end of your next turn, You have advantage on all attack rolls and your critical hit threshold is increased to 18-20. Any creature you critically hit while this Channel Divinity is active, gives you back a use of Channel Divinity.

#### Must be my Day
At 6th level, You gain 1 Luck point for the feature Lucky if you do not already have it. If you already have the Lucky feature, your total luck points you can hold increases to 4.
	Additionally, any critical hits you land against a creature deal an extra 1d6 damage of the relevant primary damage type dealt by the attack.

#### Guided Steps
Starting at 8th level, you gain advantage on all attacks of opportunity and creatures have disadvantage on all attacks of opportunity against you.
If an attack of opportunity against you misses, you gain 10 feet of movement for the remainder of your turn, and the creature who failed against has their speed reduced by 5 feet until the start of your next turn. This can only occur once per turn.

```
```

#### What are the Odds?
At 17th level, you have learned to move the threads of fate yourself and can enact one of the following actions up to 2 times. All uses of this feature are restored after a long rest.
* As a reaction, you may transform the next successful weapon attack roll of you or an ally you can see hits for double the weapon or spell damage dice.
* As a reaction to being targeted by an attack roll, you can decrease all attack rolls against you by 1d12 until the start of your next turn.
* As a reaction, you can automatically succeed on a Dexterity saving throw. If the affect would have you take half damage still, reduce that damage by 3d10.
* As part of a spell’s casting by you, you can make your target automatically fail their saving throw. This can only affect one creature if multiple creatures are targeted by the spell.


### Gaia Domain

The Gods of Earth- Grumbar, Dumathoin, Urogalan, Callarduran, and Segohan all share dominion over the essence of the world. The earth is that which all creatures were born from. From majestic dragons, to simple insects, all owe tribute to their humble beginnings and the beings that granted them life from such simple origins. The maintenance and respect for their domain is all they ask, as gods of the earth are patient, and humble, but powerful.

#### Gaia Domain Spells

| Cleric Level | Spells |
|-------|---------|
|1st|Longstrider, Thunderwave|
|3rd|Heat Metal, Locate Animals or Plants|
|5th|Conjure Barrage, Meld into Stone|
|7th|Stoneskin, Stone Shape|
|9th|Commune with Nature, Wall of Stone|


#### Bonus Cantrip
At 1st level, you learn the Mending cantrip. This works as a Cleric cantrip for you and doesn’t count against the number of cantrips you know from the Cleric Table.

#### Earth’s Salvation
Also at 1st level, You can use your action to tap into your deities creativeness and craft a simple or martial weapon and a shield from rock or stone source of at least 10 cubic feet and within 5 feet of you. The weapon you craft hits for 1d12 bludgeoning damage, regardless or the chosen form, though it adopts other properties such as finesse or two-handed. The shield acts as a normal shield would, but also reduces 1d4 damage from non-magical piercing and slashing damage.

This crafted gear breaks after 3 successful melee attacks, or 5 successful blocks against attack rolls.

At 6th level, the number of uses for the weapon increases to 4 successful melee attacks, and the shield to 6 successful blocks. The shields also reduces 1d6 damage from all piercing and slashing damage.

<div class='pageNumber'>8</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 2 | CLERIC</div>
\page

#### Channel Divinity: Seismic Blow
At 2nd level, you can use your Channel Divinity as a bonus action to empower your next successful melee attack with a weapon that deals bludgeoning damage with a force of seismic proportions.

Roll 1d10 to determine the magnitude of your blow, and add the result of your roll to the attack as force damage. If the result is 1-4, creatures within 5’ of the target take half damage from the weapon attack + seismic force, exluding you. If the result is 5-7, creatures within 5’ of the target take the full damage of the weapon attack + seismic force excluding you. If the result is an 8-10, creatures within 10’ of the target take full damage from the weapon attack + seismic force excluding you. Additionally, if you roll a 1 or 10, you regain a use of your Channel divinity in 1 minute.


#### Protection of the Earth
At 6th level, you can connect your life to the earth below to grant a haven to those in its embrace. As an action, you can touch bare rock, dirt, or grass at your feet, and the area around you within 10 feet starts to grow luscious vegetation and behaves as if you casted the Hallow spell. You can use this feature twice per long rest.

#### Toughened Mettle
Starting at 8th level, after you take damage from an attack or effect, you can use your reaction to increase your AC by 1 and reduce all damage by 3 until the end of your next turn. You can use this feature a number of times per day, equal to your Wisdom modifier. All uses of this feature recharges on a long rest.

When you reach level 14, you can increase your AC by 2 until the end of your next turn.

#### Worldly Vanguard
At 17th level, as an action you can point to a number of creatures up to your Wisdom modifier and imbue them with the protection of the land. Each affected creature gains the following benefits immediately.

* Has stoneskin cast on them
* Gains 10 temporary hit points
* Is cured of the Poisoned, Petrified, and Paralyzed condition
* Has the Bless spell cast upon them

You can use this feature once per long rest.

<div class='pageNumber'>9</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 3 | CLERIC</div>
\page

## Druid
Druids are revered as the protectors of nature, typically associated with guarding their home ecosystems and its residents. Their knowledge and wisdom allows them to be trusted more readily by the beasts of the land, and to act as envoys on their behalf when dealing with threatening forces. Some druids however have learned to harbor their worlds within themselves, opening them up to new kinds of metamorphosis and powers. These select few know and protect worlds others couldn't hope to inhabit.


### Circle of Communion
Druids of the Circle of Communion have learned to live with nature on a level beyond others. As they have met with creatures across the land, they have mixed their life energy with theirs to form mutual understanding and companionship. Using the life energy that connects all living creatures, these druids can summon in these connections for a quick assist, or to stay and help in a pinch. The more they commune with nature, the more creatures accept them and feel safe around them. This turns into friendships, respect, and an interest to keep such a creature alive. Through the fey paths that exist between realms, they watch over their wards.

#### Nature’s Entrance
At 2nd level, you gain the ability to open a hidden fey path to bring out a beast to aid you.
The beasts that you can summon depend on the Max CR you can transform into with the Wild Shape feature. As a bonus action you summon a beast of the appropriate CR, they appear in a space within 5 feet of you with a speed of 0 and get 1 attack only if they take the attack action, even if they have multi attack. They disappear at the end of your turn.

Alternatively, you can use your action to summon the creature as if using the spell Conjure Animals, but ignoring the amount of creatures summoned and the limited CR rating of the spell and instead only summoning forth a single creature. Summoned creatures can only remain for up to 1 hour, and then disappear back through the hidden fey path. They act on your turn of initiative in combat. 

You can only use this feature 2 times, and then all uses recharge on a long rest.

#### Partial Wild Shape
At 2nd level, you gain the ability to adopt certain aspects of animals you’ve communed with. You lose one use of your Wild Shape feature, and gain 4 uses of this Partial Wild Shape feature to gain an attribute of one of the listed transformations to gain their benefits at a time. As you level up, you gain access to additional Partial Wild Shapes. Unless stated, you do not adopt the creatures Statistics. Unlike the normal Wildshape where you adopt the creatures hit points and use them until they are reduced to 0, returning you to your hit points at the time of transforming, you instead just add half of the creatures hit points to your maximum hit points and current hit points until the transformation ends. While transformed, you still can cast spells.


At 2nd level, you can Partial Wild Shape one of the following attributes:

```
```

**Bear Claws:** Gain the ability to use Claws from the Black Bear stat block and its Multiattack feature as well (Does not stack with other instances of Multiattack). These replace your hands.

&nbsp;


**Crocodile Bite:** Your head transforms into that of a Crocodile and you gain the ability to use Bite from the Crocodile stat block and adopt its Strength score if it exceeds yours

&nbsp;


**Ape Arms:** Gain the ability Fist and Rock from the Ape stat block and also its climb speed. These replace your hands.

&nbsp;

Starting at 4th level, you can Partial Wild Shape one of the following attributes onto yourself:

&nbsp;

**Wolf Bite:** Your head changes to that of a wolf, and you gain the ability to use Bite from the Dire Wolf stat block and gain its Pack Tactics feature as well

&nbsp;


**Eagle Wings & Talons:** Grow wings and gain the fly speed and the ability to use Talons from the Giant Eagle stat block. These replace your hands.

&nbsp;


**Octopus Tentacles:** Gain the Tentacles ability from the Giant Octopus stat block and its Water Breathing feature as well. These replace your hands as 4 tentacles sprout from each shoulder.

&nbsp;


Starting at 8th level, you can Partial Wild Shape one of tthe following attributes onto yourself:

&nbsp;

**Boar Tusks:** Giant teeth take root in your mouth as you grow into a large size creature. Gain the ability to use Tusk from the Giant Boar stat block and its Charge feature as well

&nbsp;


**Shark Bite:** Your teeth grow in size and number as your mouth stretches and you grow into a large size creature and gain the ability to use Bite from the Hunter Shark stat block. Adopt its Strength score if it exceeds yours, and its Water Breathing feature

&nbsp;


**Quetzalcoatlus Bite:** Grow into a large size creature and gain the ability to use Bite from the Quetzalcoatlus stat block, gain its fly speed, and its Flyby feature. Your arms are replaced with wings, and your legs with a snake's tail.

#### Revealing the Paths
At 6th level, you master the fey hidden paths further and with more precision. You can now summon the beasts from Natures Entrance up to 15 feet away from you.

#### Land Swap
Beginning at 10th level, you can open up a hidden path and swap Terrain of your choice with another areas within sight. As an action, select a point you can see within 60 feet and 20 foot radius around that point is swapped with another area type of our choice of equal size. Any existing effects from spells, features, or abilities that affected the area are removed and brought to the newly swapped location. Creatures and non corporeal effects (Such as Spirit Guardians) within the area are kept in their place. The lands are returned after 1 hour or as an action.

This feature can only be used once per long rest.

<div class='pageNumber'>10</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 1 | DRUID</div>
\page




#### Mutual Survival
Starting at 14th level, your loyal animal companions feel your emotions and get protective when you get hurt. Once per long rest, when you drop below half your maximum hit point total, You may summon forth either 3 CR ½ creatures, 2 CR 1 creatures, or 1 CR 2 creature(s) to unoccupied squares within 5 feet of you. These summoned creatures only target the last creature to inflict damage on you, and disappear after a turn passes where no creatures who have harmed you during this encounter remain. They also will leave if they are reduced to 0 hit points, the encounter ends, or you are reduced to 0 hit points. They act on your turn of initiative but cannot move more than 5 feet away from you.

### Circle of the Ocean

Druids of the Circle of the Ocean have felt a deep connection with the vast array of life at sea. Immersing themselves amongst the ocean has given them an understanding of the creatures of the deep that others could not fathom. Their natural magic from the sea is teeming with attributes not seen anywhere else, and even better they can bring them onto land.

#### Underwater Resident
At 2nd level, your connection with nature has taught you how to change your body to adapt to aquatic life. As an action, you can focus on growing gills and webbed hands and feet. Doing so gives you the features Darkvision for 60 feet, a Swim speed of 25 feet, and have the Water Breathing spell cast on you for this features duration. You also have advantage on all Dexterity saving throws made while in water. These changes last for 8 hours or can be ended early as an action.
This feature can be used twice per long rest. You gain an additional use of  this feature at 6th level, and gain an additional 10 feet of swim speed at 10th level.

#### Aquatic Wild Shape
Also at 2nd level, You are able to combine some extra magic into your aquatic nature Wild Shapes. Anytime you Wild Shape into a creature with the Water Breathing or Amphibious feature, you can choose to immediately cause your new form to hover above the ground, as if casting the spell Levitate on yourself, but with a vertical limit of 5 feet.

#### Circle Spells
Your mystical connection to the ocean infuses you with the ability to cast certain spells. At 3rd, 5th, 7th, and 9th level you gain access to Ocean Spells connected to the source that helped you become a druid.
Once you gain access to an Ocean spell, you always have it prepared, and it doesn’t count against the number of spells you can prepare each day. If you gain access to a spell that doesn’t appear on the Druid Spell list, the spell is nonetheless a druid spell for you.

#### Circle of the Ocean spell list
| Druid Level | Spells |
|-------|---------|
|3rd|Alter Self, Misty Step|
|5th|Water Walk, Water Breathing|
|7th|Control Water, Ice Storm|
|9th|Conjure Elemental, Cone of Cold|

&nbsp;

#### Bring me the Sea
At 6th level, you can mentally connect the land around you to the sea and swap the two out. As an action, select a 30 foot by 15 foot area of flat ground, and a 15 foot deep trench appears there filled with ocean water. The transformed ground lasts for 10 minutes and is then seamlessly undone. Creatures within the transformed area at the time of it returning to normal are simply raised up to ground level as it returns.

#### Hastened Evolution
Beginning at 10th level, your changes from the Underwater Resident feature gains new abilities. Whenever you transform with the Underwater Resident feature, select two of the following properties to adopt alongside the other changes.
* Channel Bioelectric features from sea life. Add 1d8 lightning damage to all melee attacks.
* Channel camouflage capabilities from stealthy ocean creatures. As a bonus action, turn invisible until the start of your next turn. The invisibility ends if you make an attack roll, cast a spell, or are damaged.
* Harden the exterior of your skin to resemble the hide of deep sea animals. Your base AC without armor becomes 14 + Dex modifier
* Gain teeth and jaw strength to rival the predators of the deep. Your unarmed melee attacks become a Bite attack that deals 2d6 piercing damage

<div class='pageNumber'>11</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 2 | DRUID</div>

\page

#### Creature of the Deep
Starting at 14th level, You can use one of your charges of Wildshape to assume the form of a Lesser Kraken with the stats listen below.

