## Fighter
Being a warrior means to survive and grow. Every creature is where it is today by being a fighter in some regard. But nowadays, people train to meet a standard of performance for some baron or royalty. Fighting becomes stale, and the arts of perfecting every last movement becomes muddied amongst the numbers of armies. Save for a few, who seek to perfect their craft and excel in skillsets specialized to their abilities.


### Spear Master
The spear is one of the oldest weapons of the hunt. It has been seen in all the great battles of old, and serves today as a symbol of power, protection, and skill. Through mastery of this weapon, control of the battlefield is yours to command. With a spear and shield in hand, no threat presents itself that you cannot try to out maneuver.


#### Spear Maneuvers
Starting at 3rd level, You gain the use of 3 Spear Maneuvers of your choice, which are detailed under “ Spear Maneuvers” below. Many maneuvers enhance an attack in some way. You can use only one maneuver per attack. 
You learn two additional maneuvers of your choice at 7th, 10th level. Each time you learn new maneuvers, you can also replace one maneuver you know with a different one. 

Superiority Dice. You have four superiority dice, which are d8s. A superiority die is expended when you use it. You regain all of your expended superiority dice when you finish a short or long rest. You gain another superiority die at 7th level and one more at 15th level.

Saving Throws. Some of your maneuvers require your target to make a saving throw to resist the maneuver’s effects. The saving throw DC is calculated as follows:

Maneuver save DC = 8 + your proficiency bonus + your Strength or Dexterity modifier (your choice)


#### Maneuvers

**Broadened Guard:**
You can expend one superiority die and use your reaction to guard you and any adjacent allies. While you are wielding a shield and an adjacent ally is the target of a melee attack within 5 feet, you can add half of your superiority die (minimum of 1) to their AC. This can be done only before the outcome of the attack is determined.

&nbsp;

**Charge:**
As an action, you can expend a superiority die to move up to your movement speed plus 10 feet in a straight line if you haven’t used any of your movement yet. As part of this action, you can make a weapon attack with a spear after having moved at least 20 feet. If that attack hits successfully, add 1d6 + your superiority die result to the damage.

&nbsp;

**Crippling Wound:**
You can expend one superiority die to precisely plant your spear into a weak spot on an opponent. As part of a successful weapon attack roll, you can spend a superiority die to reduce the creatures movement speed, fly speed, and or swim speed to 5ft. until the end of their next turn. Additionally, they have disadvantage on their next melee attack roll. For this attack, add the superiority die to the attack’s damage roll.

&nbsp;

**Decisive Blow:**
Trying to end things quickly, you attempt a finishing blow on your opponent. As a weapon attack roll with a spear, by spending one superiority die, you increase your Critical Hit threshold to 18-20 for that attack. Add the superiority die to the attack’s damage roll.

&nbsp;

**Feinting Attack:**
You can expend one superiority die and use a bonus action on your turn to feint, choosing one creature within 5 feet of you as your target. You have advantage on your next attack roll against that creature this turn. If that attack hits, add the superiority die to the attack’s damage roll and that creature cannot make opportunity attacks until the start of your next turn.

&nbsp;

**Flurry:**
With deadly precision and furious speed, you make multiple attacks on your opponent. By expanding one superiority die as an action while wielding a spear, you can make a number of attack rolls at a target within range equal to the result of the superiority die. The damage for each of these attacks is 1d4 piercing damage +Strength modifier.

&nbsp;

**Lunging Strike:**
When you make a melee weapon attack on your turn, you can expend one superiority die to increase your reach for that attack by 5 feet. If you hit, you add the superiority die to the attack’s damage roll.

&nbsp;

**Menacing Attack:**
When you hit a creature with a weapon attack, you can expend one superiority die to attempt to frighten the target. You add the superiority die to the attack’s damage roll, and the target must make a Wisdom saving throw. On a failed save, it is frightened of you until the end of your next turn.

&nbsp;

**Overhead Attack:**
Raising your spear up high, you bring it down over our opponent. When you make a weapon attack roll with a spear, you can spend one superiority die to add +2 to the attack roll. If this attack roll is successful, your target must succeed on a Strength saving throw. On a failed save, they are knocked prone.

&nbsp;

**Pinning Wound:**
Either by thrusting or throwing your spear, you attempt to halt your opponent in their tracks. By spending one superiority die, you can pin your spear through your target and force them to make a Dexterity saving throw. On a failed save, the target is Restrained and takes Piercing damage equal to the result of the Superiority die. Add half of the superiority die (minimum of 1) to the saving throw DC. This DC persists for all future Strength checks by a creature to remove the spear. This action disarms you of your spear. 

&nbsp;

**Skewer Toss:**
Jabbing your target at the tip of your spear, you are able to make an unconventional attack. After you successfully make a weapon attack roll with a spear against a medium or smaller creature within 5 feet, you can spend one superiority die to throw the creature at another target up to 10 feet away. The new target must make a Dexterity saving throw. On a fail, both creatures are knocked prone, and take damage equal to the result of the superiority die. On a save, the newly targeted creature takes half damage and is not knocked prone. The original target still is knocked prone and takes damage equal to the result of the superiority die.
 

<div class='pageNumber'>14</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 1 | FIGHTER</div>
\page

**Sweeping Attack:**
When you hit a creature with an attack roll made with a spear, you can expend one superiority die to attempt to damage up to another 2 creatures with the same attack. Choose one or two creatures within 5 feet of the original target and within your reach. If the original attack roll would hit the newly selected creature(s), they take damage equal to the number you roll on your superiority die. The damage is of the same type dealt by the original attack.
 
&nbsp;

**Trip Attack:**
When you hit a creature with an attack roll made with a spear, you can expend one superiority die to attempt to knock the target down. You add the superiority die to the attack’s damage roll, and if the target is Large or smaller, it must make a Strength saving throw. On a failed save, you knock the target prone.
 
&nbsp;

**Pushing Attack:**
When you hit a creature with an attack roll made with a spear, you can expend one superiority die to attempt to drive the target back. You add the superiority die to the attack’s damage roll, and if the target is Large or smaller, it must make a Strength saving throw. On a failed save, you push the target up to 15 feet away from you.
 
&nbsp;

**Parry:**
When another creature damages you with a melee attack, you can use your reaction and expend one superiority die to reduce the damage by the number you roll on your superiority die + your Dexterity modifier.

#### Tip of the Spear
Starting at 7th level, Spears gain the Finesse property when wielded by you. Also, if you spend a bonus action, you can make your attack rolls into Lunging Strikes until the end of your turn. You can only use this feature once per long rest.

#### Deadly Toss
At 10th level, your deadliness with the spear increases to an uncanny expertise. When you use your spear as part of a thrown weapon attack, the range is increased by 30 feet and you add +3 to your attack roll for this attack. Your critical hit threshold is increased to 19-20 as well. 

#### Improved Combat Superiority
At 15th level, your superiority dice turn into d12s.

#### Exampliary charge
At 18th level, when you first enter an encounter, you take the initiative in battle to set the tone. You can choose to gain a +3 bonus to your initiative, and for the first round you will gain the following benefits:
* You gain an additional 10 feet of movement speed.
* On a single successful  weapon attack roll, you may apply a free use of any Spear Maneuver without spending a superiority die.
* You gain a +1 bonus to AC.
* You do not trigger attacks of opportunity.
* Allies within 5ft. of you at the start of your turn gain 1d6 temporary hit points

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

### Tempest Blade

Though you have access to the arcane, trying to bring it forth the ways a sorcerer or wizard might has proven fruitless. Instead, your blade in battle is where it naturally comes forth, and so you let it blossom on the field in physical combat. Thunder booms, wounds chill over, and lightning cracks as your blade rips through foes. Even your movements gain aid from these forces of nature that swell within you. Whenever you enter the field, the enemy knows a storm is approaching.


#### The Calm
Starting at 3rd level, some of the magical energy within you builds up as you take hits, getting ready to unleash itself in a devastating form. As you take hits, you will roll 1d4 per hit and gain the following Charge as listed below.
No charge is gained

* 1 charge of of Thunder damage is generated
* 1 charge of Cold damage is generated
* 1 charge of Lightning damage is generated

You can store up to 3 charges, and all charges are lost at the end of your turn. 1 charge of your choice can be added to your next attack roll, but are lost if your attack misses. Each charge provides an additional 1d4 damage of the relevant type. You can store up to 4 charges at 10th level, and at 18th level, the charges now deal for 1d10 damage of the relevant type.

#### Technical Block
Starting at 7th level, You can take the chance of a risky block to allow yourself to get better positioning.
When you are the target of a melee attack roll, before the roll is made you can use your reaction to attempt a Technical Block. By performing a Technical Block, you try to directly block the attack with your weapon, instead of dodging or using a shield. This lowers your AC for the attack by 2, but if the attack against you fails, the following benefits take effect until the end of your next turn. 
* The attacking creature’s speed is reduced to 0.
* You gain advantage on all attack rolls against the creature.
* The creature cannot benefit from the Multiattack feature until the start of its next turn.
* You can choose to swap locations with the attack creature.

#### Storm the Lines
At 10th level, You can use your bonus action to Dash, as magical winds propel you forward. All creatures who are within 5 feet of you when you first take the Dash action with this feature take 1d4 cold damage. You can use this feature a number of times equal to your Wisdom modifier (Minimum of 1). All uses of this feature recharge on a short or long rest

#### Lightning Fueled
At 15th level, Your muscles course with lightning at all times, allowing you to hasten your reactions and gain resistance to Lightning damage. Whenever you perform an attack of opportunity, instead of a normal melee weapon attack, you can unleash a flurry of slashes. Roll 1d6 and you can make that many attack rolls against the creature. The weapon die for all of these attacks becomes a 1d6 . This ability can only be used once per encounter.


<div class='pageNumber'>15</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 2 | FIGHTER</div>
\page

#### Storm Stance
At 18th level, You become a weapon of nature as lightning leaks from your eyes, and you hover above the ground, held aloft by cycloning winds. As an action, you can enter Storm Stance and gain the following benefits.

* Your movement speed is increased by 10 feet, and you are no longer affected by difficult terrain.
* Before making an attack roll, you can spend 3 charges of The Calm to attack all creatures within a 30 foot cone originating from you with the attack.
* All of your elemental damage dice from The Calm and the Lightning Fueled features inflict an additional 1d4 damage.

Storm Stance lasts for 1 minutes or until you end it with a free action. This feature can only be used once before it needs to recharge with a long rest.

### Shield Knight

Knights are often touted as champions of battles, slaying enemies left and right with little error. While this can be true, it is a romanticized version of the title that misses the key aspect of becoming a knight. One becomes a knight to protect that which they value above all else. They are the sword of their master when necessary, but always their shield. A knight who cannot defend that which matters, is worthy to only be called a soldier at best. In service to that which matters, a shield knight stands firm in the face of any and all opposition.

#### Shield of the People
Starting at 3rd level, You gain the strength to stand against all threats. All shields for you now can be used in attack rolls as an offhand weapon if you are wielding a weapon in the other hand, or on their own as simple weapons. Shields gain the Versatile property for you when used as weapons, and do damage based on their material. Wooden shields hit for 1d6 bludgeoning damage (1d8 versatile) , metal shields hit for 1d8 bludgeoning damage (1d10 versatile), and adamantine shields hit for 1d10 bludgeoning damage (1d12 versatile). Unless stated otherwise, most shields are metal.

Additionally, you can use your reaction to add +2 AC to any ally that is within 5 feet of you who is the target of a melee or ranged attack before the attack roll is made. While wielding a shield however, your speed is lowered by 5 feet.

```
```

#### Wall Assault
At 7th level, your shield is no longer just a means of protecting, but also a proper offensive option. You gain 1 use of each of the following maneuvers per long rest so long as you are wielding a shield. The DC for creatures to save against for some of your abilities is equal to (8 + Proficiency bonus + Strength modifier).

&nbsp;


**Bulldozer:** As an action, you can stampede up to 20 feet in a straight line, assaulting everyone along your path. Make an attack roll with your shield against all creatures within your line or who are within 5 feet of it. On a successful attack, that creature must succeed on a Strength saving throw, or be knocked prone. This movement does not provoke attacks of opportunity

&nbsp;


**Rebuttal:** In response to a creature failing a melee attack roll against you from within 5 ft, you may attack them immediately after as a free action with a shield. This attack gets a +1 bonus to the attack roll and damage roll for every bonus to AC your shield grants.

&nbsp;


**Immovable:** As a reaction, you can choose to cancel the effects of an action that would cause you to be moved against your will up to 15 feet, drop prone, or become disarmed.

&nbsp;

**Shield Toss:** As an action, you can throw your shield at an enemy within 15 feet as a weapon attack. This attack does an extra weapon die of damage on a successful hit. Whether your attack is successful or not, your shield drops into the nearest unoccupied space between you and the target.

&nbsp;

You gain a second use of each of these actions per long rest at 10th level.

#### Guardian Will
At 10th level, Your body and mind are one in resolution, allowing you to withstand further threats of even a mystical nature. Add your Constitution modifier to any Wisdom saving throws while you are wielding a shield. 

#### Mountainous Resolve
At 15th level, Your body is used to punishment and is now quite adept at taking it. 2 times per long rest, you can reduce 2d6 damage from an attack that has harmed you as a reaction. Additionally, if you were to be reduced to 0 hit points or less, after reducing the damage from an attack, you instead are reduced to 1 hit point, dropping all held and wielded items and falling prone.

#### Aegis
At 18th level, You can use your bonus action to bolster your body and mind against all threats. Until the start of your next turn, you mitigate 10+2d10 damage from all sources of damage. This can be used once per long rest.

<div class='pageNumber'>16</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 3 | FIGHTER</div>
\page

## Monk

Through self exploration, it isn't hard to see that many a practitioner of monk traditions would awaken to unique and powerful control over their Ki and body. Some wield tremendous forces of nature through their own control, while others tune their body into the natural state of flow of lifes energy. Whether in peace, or through duty, they each are forces of ferocity and respect.

### Way of Lightning

What many a monk calls Ki, or a spiritualist calls soul, Monks of the way of lightning recognize this latent potential as the dormant biology that the body can obtain. Life is energy, and energy turned physical becomes lightning, one needs only to truly understand this to reach out to this source. By doing so, the limits of the body are released, and your life force becomes an existential weapon or defense for you to manipulate.

#### Charged Dash
Starting at 3rd level, whenever you use your Step of the Wind feature, you can now move quickly enough to move through a creatures square unhindered by difficult terrain and without meeting the 2 sizes larger or smaller requirement. Any creature you pass through in this manner is hit for 1d4 lightning damage. If you use this feature, you gain resistance to lightning damage for 1 minute.

#### Lightning Reflexes
Also at 3rd level, your reactions to danger are increased by lightning coursing through your muscles. When you are the target of a melee attack roll, you can use your reaction and a Ki Point to impose disadvantage on the attack. If the attack misses, you can make 1 unarmed strike against that attacking creature if they are within range. If you use this feature, you gain resistance to lightning damage for 1 minute.

#### Electric Disruption
At 6th level, you can charge up an unarmed strike attack with pure electrical energy. Spend 3 ki points, and gain +1d4 lightning damage for all unarmed strikes for 1 minute. Creatures harmed by unarmed strikes charged by this feature have their Dexterity score reduced by 1 for 5 minutes up to a maximum of 2. The lightning damage increases to 1d16 at 11th level.

#### Channel Lightning
Starting at 11th level, your body can now charge more electrical energy than it can handle. As an action, you can now spend 3 ki points to cast the spell Lightning Bolt, or 5 Ki points to cast the spell Chain Lightning without the material components.

```
```

#### Lightning Body
Starting at 17th level, you can overload your body with electricity and maintain it around you so that you now are living lightning. By expending 5 ki points, you can transform for 1 minute and gain the following benefits.

* Your movement speed is increased by 15 feet and you can move through a space as narrow as 1 inch wide without squeezing. A creature that touches you or hits you with a melee attack while within 5 feet takes 3 lightning damage.
* You also have advantage on all Dexterity saving throws.

* You shed bright light in a 30-foot radius and dim light in an additional 30 feet.

* You are immune to lightning damage

* If you touch at least a 5 cubic foot body of water, you electrocute it but at the cost of some of your power. All creatures within 5 feet of the point you touch the water take 2d12 lightning damage, creatures within 10 feet take 2d10 lightning damage, and creatures within 15 feet take 2d8 lightning damage. Creatures only take damage from the largest damage die amount based on their proximity, not a collective amount. When this is done however, you take 2d4 force damage and end your lightning form.

<div class='pageNumber'>17</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 1 | MONK</div>
\page

## Way of the Runic Body

### Sacred Body
Starting at 3rd level, you unlock certain blocks on your Ki, and runes appear as engravings on your body. Your first Ki you unlock engraves your wrists and forearms and adds 1d4 force damage to all hits with Flurry of Blows. This increases to 2d4 at 11th level and 3d4 at 17th level.

#### Chakra Sync
Additionally at 3rd level, you become accustomed to the raw arcane energy in the world as it mingles with you Ki, granting you Proficiency in Arcana (Wisdom) skill checks. You can now cast Detect Magic as an action for 2 Ki Points. And you can also regenerate a Ki Point if you reduce a creature with an unused spell slot to 0 hit points with an unarmed strike. 

#### Awakened Step
At 6th level, you unlock another block on your Ki as engravings appear on your feet, granting your movements an element borderlining levitation.

Your Runes now glow a dim white light that spreads out in a 10 foot radius of you for 5 minutes after using a Ki point.

After you use 3 Ki Points within 1 minute of each other, you gain the following benefits for 3 rounds: 
* Your footsteps become silent.
* You ignore non-magical difficult terrain. 
* You gain 10 feet of movement speed if you are not receiving additional movement speed from any spells
* You can teleport 1 time up to 10 feet to a place you can see as a reaction to being targeted by an attack roll by succeeding on a Dexterity saving throw equal to 12 + the attacking creatures Dex. modifier.

Using another Ki Point while you are still benefiting from this effect prolongs the effect by an additional turn.

At 17th level, your teleport is increased to 20 feet.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

```
```



#### Durable Body
Starting at 11th level, Your next Ki is unlocked and engravings appear on your back. After you hit a creature with Flurry of Blows, you increase your AC by 1 for each successful hit you land until the start of your next turn. This can only occur once per round.

#### Unchained Weapon
Starting at 17th level, new engravings connect all your previous ones, along with a new one on the back of your head. This is your ultimate state, improving your ability to control how much Ki you use. You gain the following abilities

* You can now spend 1 ki point to see all invisible creatures within 20 feet for 1 hour.

* Once every hour upon entering combat, you gain 1 Ki point up to your maximum number of Ki points.

* As an action you can cast Detect Thoughts without the material component one time. This ability recharges on a long rest.

* If you choose to spend an additional Ki point during Flurry of Blows, it gains 2d6 Psychic damage on a successful hit and the creature must succeed on a Strength Saving Throw against your Ki save. On a fail they are pushed back 10 feet.


### Way of the Lotus Palm

#### Gentle Grace
Starting at 3rd level, your form and movements have a gentle air about them. Your movement is not hampered by non-magical difficult terrain. You also gain a Climb speed of 15 ft and damage you would take from falling beyond 10 feet is reduced to using d4’s as the damage dice.

#### Magical Touch
Additionally at 3rd level, you know two cantrips of your choice from the Cleric spell list. The Way of the Lotus Palm table shows how many spell slots you have to cast your cleric spells of 1st level and higher. To cast one of these spells, you must expend a slot of the spell’s level or higher. You regain all expended spell slots when you finish a long rest.

You prepare the list of Cleric spells that are available for you to cast, choosing from the cleric spell list. When you do so, choose a number of cleric spells equal to your Wisdom modifier + Charisma modifier. The spells must be of a level for which you have spell slots.

You can change your list of prepared spells when you finish a long rest. Preparing a new list of cleric spells requires time spent in prayer and meditation: at least 1 minute per spell level for each spell on your list.


<div class='pageNumber'>18</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 2 | MONK</div>
\page

