#### Aura of Light
At 20th level, your presence alone speaks for you to announce that you are the champion of your deity. As a reaction when you are dropped below half of your maximum hit points, all undead creatures and abominations that can see you have disadvantage on all Attack Rolls and Saving Throws. This effect lasts for 1 minute.

Additionally, you may spend a use of Channel Divinity at this time to become infused by your deity while in Aura of Light. This grants you the following features.

* You emit an aura of light that extends for 30 feet, and an aura of dim light that extends another 30 feet beyond that.
* Creatures you have damaged, or have damaged you, who start their turn in your aura of light take 1d4 Radiant damage.
* You can use your action to cast a level 1 Cure Wounds spell on all creatures you choose who are touched by your Aura of Light. This can only be used once per use of Aura of Light
* If your mount is within your Aura of Light, it gains 2d10 temporary hit points and +2 AC
* If your mount drops to 0 hit points while within your aura of light, it instead is dropped to 1 hit point, is teleported to a location up to 60 feet away from you that you can see, and is Petrified in a golden metal until it is touched by your Holy Symbol, or 24 hours passes.

<div class='pageNumber'>23</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 3 | PALADIN</div>
\page
### Oath of Liberation

Paladins who pursue the Oath of the Liberation seek to free the souls of all from anything holding them down. Freedom and free will are the truest treasures of life and those who would rob an individual of that must be halted from doing so. Whatever is for the greater good is what the Paladin will ultimately choose on how to ensure the freedom of others, but will resort to killing as a last resort, as it is the ultimate act of theft. Tyrants should beware their methods and practices when a Paladin of Liberation gets wind of them, as they are famous for leading the people to new eras of freedom.

#### Tenents of Devotion
Though the exact words and strictures of the Oath of Liberation vary per path, paladins of this oath typically share these tenets.

&nbsp;


**Courage.** Through fear of death we see ourselves for who we truly are. And I shall not run from my fears.

&nbsp;


**Honor.** I need not unsheath my weapon without reason, but I shall not wield it without valor.

&nbsp;


**Free Will.** Each life is precious in that it can be lived however it wants. Others have no right to say otherwise.

&nbsp;


**The People’s Champion.** To be a paladin, one must be the paladin of the people. You are their holy sword and shield in the face of injustice and malice in the world. 


#### Channel Divinity
When you take this oath at 3rd level, you gain the following two Channel Divinity Options 

#### Brand of the Oppressor
As an action, you can use your Channel Divinity to try and mark a number of creatures equal to your Charisma modifier that you can see within 60 feet with the Brand of the Oppressor.

Selected creatures must succeed on a Wisdom saving throw or be branded with a black and red sigil on their body. Creatures with the Brand of the Oppressor cannot impose disadvantage onto creatures through the effects of spells or features and cannot benefit from advantage on attack rolls, ability checks, or saving throws. If a creature with a Mark of the Oppressor causes another creature to become Paralyzed, Restrained, or Stunned, they too are affected by the same condition at that time.

This mark lasts as long as the creatures remain within 60 feet of you, or after 5 minutes passes.

#### Barrier of Cleansing
As a reaction, you can use your Channel Divinity to select up to 3 allies within 60 feet to be surrounded by a white and yellow sphere of energy.

These allies are immediantly cleansed of all conditions except Incapacitated and Unconscious, and have the spells Featherfall and Resistance cast on them. If the creatures were Restrained or Grappled, they move 5 feet into the nearest unoccupied space.


```
```

##### Oath of the Valkyrie Spells
| Paladin Level | Spells |
|:----:|:-------------|
| 3rd  | Command, Hunter's Mark |
| 5th  | Hold Person, Silence |
| 9th  | Beacon of Hope, Fear |
| 13th | Freedom of Movement, Death Ward |
| 17th | Awaken, Dominate Person |

#### Aura of Freedom
Starting at 7th level, you and allies within 20 feet of you cannot have their movement reduced or be Restrained by magical means. They also have advantage against any checks to escape grapples.
At 18th level, your aura’s range increases to 30 feet.

#### Retribution of the Slave
Starting at 15th level, you can use your divine presence to free allies who have had their freedom stolen from them. While an ally within 10 feet of you is charmed, you can use your reaction to end the charm immediately and cause 2d6 psychic damage against the source of the charm.

#### Liberation
At 20th level, you become the beacon of freedom, and the nightmare of oppressors. As a bonus action, you can swear an oath to the free will of life to gain the following benefits for 1 minute:

Your Aura of Freedom increases to 40 feet in range and now grants immunity to Fear
You are immune to becoming Paralyzed or Stunned.
All allies who start their turn within your Aura of Freedom have the spell Heroism cast upon them once per encounter and gain 10 feet of movement speed until the end of their turn.

When you or a creature within your Aura of Freedom is the target of a melee attack roll, you can ask the DM if the attacking creatures Strength modifier is higher than the target creatures. If the attacking creatures Strength modifier is indeed higher than the target creatures, the attacking creature loses their proficiency bonus to their attack roll if it was benefiting from it.

<div class='pageNumber'>24</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 4 | PALADIN</div>
\page

## Ranger

With the passing of time, the traditional huntsman has had to adapt to the ever changing environment. New tricks have been developed and passed down as time has marched forward, breeding new types of rangers into the wild. With each generation, the bar of skill is raised higher, and the precision of their aim is as sharp as their wit. Whatever methods they implore, you should hope that one of them is never on your trail.

### Urban Grounds
The idea that a ranger is one who skulks the woods and wilds is outdated and so limiting. There are so many skills that a city can teach you that can't be learned without strangers around. the name of the game is the same, but now you need to outsmart others who can scheme and think, not just the instincts of a beast. Besides, what is a city besides a jungle within walls.


#### Local hunter
At 3rd level, you learn Thieves Cant and choose one of the following features. You gain another feature from this selection at 11th level.

&nbsp;


**City Scaler.**
Gain a climb speed of 30 feet and proficiency in Acrobatics (Dex) and Athletics (Str)

&nbsp;


**Blending in.**
Gain the spells Disguise Self and Expeditious Retreat as Ranger spells.

&nbsp;


**Local Gossip.**
Gain advantage on any Charisma skill checks or Charisma saving throws against non hostile targets.

&nbsp;


**Born behind walls.**
While in an urban setting, your movement speed is increased by 10 feet. You can use your bonus action to take the Dash, Dodge, or Disengage action if a hostile creature is within 5 feet.

#### Relentless
At 7th level, you can unleash a storm of projectiles at a foe with every move they make. 

As an action, target a creature within range, and make 2 weapon attack rolls against them. If either of these attacks hit, you can  use your reaction on that creatures turn to make attacks rolls with advantage on that creature at the start of their movement and again at the end of their movement so long as you still can make the attacks against them.

If the creature does not move, you cannot make these attacks. You can use this feature 2 times per long rest.

```
```



#### Improvised Position
At 11th level, you now have an unique understanding of how to use height and obstructions to your advantage. You no longer suffer from disadvantage on attack rolls with ranged weapons from being prone. This only applies against a target if they are no more than 5 feet above you.

#### Adaptation
At 15th level, your expertise at navigating a city improves. Choose three of the following features to gain. You can change 1 feature you benefit from by spending 8 hours exploring and examining an area.

&nbsp;


**Evasion.** When you are subjected to an effect, such as a red dragon’s fiery breath or a lightning bolt spell, that allows you to make a Dexterity saving throw to take only half damage, you instead take no damage if you succeed on the saving throw and only half the damage if you fail. You cannot gain this feature alongside Uncanny Dodge.

&nbsp;


**Uncanny Dodge.** When an attacker that you can see hits you with an attack, you can use your reaction to halve the attack’s damage against you. You cannot gain this feature alongside Evasion.

&nbsp;


**Sticky Fingers.** You can add your Charisma modifier to any Sleight of Hand skill checks and when you use your action to make a Sleight of Hand check in combat, you gain advantage if you were not the target of the creatures last attack.

&nbsp;


**Blending in.** Gain a +5 bonus to all Stealth rolls.

&nbsp;


**Pick from a Crowd.** Gain a +5 bonus to Perception skill checks.

&nbsp;


**Alleyway Scrapper.** When you have solid walls at least 10 feet tall on at least 2 sides of you within 10 feet, you gain a +1 to AC and a +1 to attack rolls and saving throws. Additionally, you do not suffer from attacks of opportunity if both you and the creature are in these conditions.

<div class='pageNumber'>25</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 1 | RANGER</div>
\page

### Trapper
What many of the local hunters seem to have forgotten is the value of patience when pursueing prey. Meticulously tracking your quarry and learning their habits puts you in a mindset fit to have them trigger their own demise. But digging pits and laying net traps is how the old world did things, as Trapper's nowadays have the means to magically create their own, with a twist. Never pursue a trapper unless you plan to follow tem by tiptoeing the whole way.

#### Arcane Traps
At 3rd level, as an action you can place a magical sigil on unoccupied flat ground within 5 feet of you by touching that area. The sigil is hidden by illusion and is only seen by you unless detected by magic, or seen by creatures that can see invisible objects. The sigil takes up a full 5 foot diameter area and can have nothing in the area when it is placed but can then be covered by objects or creatures.

A trap is triggered when a creature is directly above the sigil and you use a Reaction to activate it. You are aware when a creature is over the sigil, but no other specifics as to what the creature is or who it is.

A trap lasts for 8 hours and then dissipates, or if Dispel Magic is cast on it. You may only have one trap active at a time, and laying a new trap erases the old one. You can also spend 5 minutes to remove an unused trap and not have it deplete a use of this feature. Any saving throws required by your traps uses your Spell save DC.

&nbsp;


You learn 3 types of traps to start from the options below. You learn 2 more at 7th level, another 2 at 11th level, and 1 more at 15th level. Each time you learn a new trap, you can replace any trap you know with a different one.

You can use this feature a number of times equal to 1 + your Wisdom modifier (a minimum of 1). You regain all expended uses on a long rest.

At 11th level, all traps that cause damage gain an additional 1d4 of their respective damage types.


#### Traps
**Crippling Trap.** When this trap is activated, the creature within it must make a Dexterity saving throw. On a fail, the detonating creatures body stiffens and they then grant advantage to any melee attack rolls against them and have disadvantage on all melee attack rolls and Dexterity saving throws until the end of its next turn.

At 9th level, the Dexterity saving throw requirement against this trap increases by 1.

&nbsp;


**Elemental Trap.**  When this trap is activated, the target creature within it must make a Dexterity saving throw. On a fail, they take 2d4 damage of fire, cold, acid, poison, lightning, or thunder; your choice. The damage the must be chosen at the time of the traps creation. On a save, the creature takes half damage.

At 9th level, this damage increases to 3d4.

```
```

**Launching Trap.** When this trap is activated, the creature within it must make a Dexterity saving throw. On a fail, The creature is launched high into the sky if it is a Medium or smaller creature. Roll 1d4, and the creature is launched into the air a number of feet as based on the result:
1. 10 feet
2. 20 feet
3. 20 feet and up to 5 feet in any other direction
4. 30 feet and up to 10 feet in any other direction

If the creature is Large or larger or on a successful save, they are unaffected by this trap. Should a launched creature land on another creature, that second creature must succeed on a Dexterity saving throw, or take 1d6 bludgeoning damage for every 10 feet the initial creature fell onto them. On a save they take no damage. The initial creature is moved to an unoccupied square after the saving throw is attempted.

At 9th level, an additional 10 feet in height is added to all outcomes.

&nbsp;

**Magnetic Trap.** When this trap is activated, if the offending creature within it is wearing or wielding metal, it must make a Strength saving throw. On a fail, The creature is forcefully pulled to the ground Prone. The creature remains prone until it succeeds on its Strength Saving throw on subsequent turns or If the creature doffs its metal armor, and or drops its metal weapon. The effect lasts for 2 turns.

At 9th level, the Strength saving throw requirement against this trap increases by 1.

&nbsp;


**Pitfall Trap.** This trap can only be placed above an area of dirt at least 10 feet deep. When this trap is activated, the creature within it must make a Dexterity saving throw. On a fail, a 5 foot diameter trench opens up below the creature to 10 feet down as if affected by the Move Earth spell. The creature takes any appropriate falling damage and is then sealed in from above and an X is drawn into the above earth over the pocket underground. The earth above has hit points equal to 4 times your Ranger level and once depleted crumbles so the trench is no longer sealed. On a successful save, the creature moves to an unoccupied space within 5 feet.

At 9th level, the Dexterity saving throw requirement against this trap increases by 1.

<div class='pageNumber'>26</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 2 | RANGER</div>
\page

**Repulsive Trap.** When this trap is activated, the creature within it and all creatures within 5 feet must make a Dexterity saving throw. On a fail, A shockwave generates from the sigil, dealing 2d4+1 force damage to all creatures within 5 feet and launching the creature above the sigil 10 feet in a direction of your choosing so long as it is Large or smaller. On a save, half damage is taken and the creature is not pushed away if it was subject to that effect.

At 9th level, the damage increases to 3d4+1 force damage


**Shielding Trap.** When this trap is activated, the creature within it gains Mage Armor and a +1 bonus to its AC on top of its new AC from Mage Armor until the end of its next turn.

At 9th level, the bonus to AC increases to +2.

&nbsp;


**Smokescreen Trap.** This trap detonates into an opaque mist, as if casting the spell Fog Cloud. The detonating creature is then made invisible until the start of your next turn.

At 9h level, the creature remains invisible for 1 additional round, though invisibility can still be ended early as outlined in the spell Invisibility
    


**Snaring Trap.** When this trap is activated, the creature within it must make a Dexterity saving throw. On a fail, the sigil rises off the ground and wraps around the creature, before tethering itself to the ground and Restraining the creature. Restrained creatures may attempt to make their subsequent saving throws at the end of their subsequent turns to break free.

At 9th level, the Dexterity saving throw requirement against this trap increases by 1.

&nbsp;


**Stored Spell Trap.** You can infuse this trap with a 2nd level or lower spell that is released upon detonation and treats the creature above the sigil as the target of the spell. All spell effects use your Spell attack roll and Spell saving throw DC.

At 9th level, you can store up to a 3rd level spell within this trap.

&nbsp;


**Swift Interruption Trap.** You can place this Trap as a bonus action instead of an action When this trap is activated, the creature within it must make a Dexterity saving throw. On a fail, it takes 1d6+1 force damage and has its speed reduced to 0 until the start of its next turn. On a save, they take half damage and do not have their speed reduced.

At 9th level, the Dexterity saving throw requirement against this trap increases by 1.

&nbsp;


**Vampiric Trap.** When this trap is activated, the creature within it must make a Dexterity saving throw. On a fail, The creature takes 2d6 necrotic damage and then the sigil becomes visible by a dim yellow light. The next creature other than the detonating creature to step on the sigil is healed for the inflicted damage. If the next creature to touch the sigil is undead, they instead take the inflicted amount as Radiant damage.

At 9th level, the damage increases to 3d6 necrotic damage.

```
```

#### Trap Advantage
At 7th level, you can now see in your mind what type of creature has entered your sigils range, but not details. Additionally, If you use your action to place a sigil on your turn, you can use your bonus action to make one weapon attack roll.

#### Seamless Placement
At 11th level, you can use your bonus action to move your sigil up to 15 feet in any direction to a place you can see. Sigils can also now be placed on any flat surface like a ceiling or wall, but cannot travel to a new surface place like from the floor to a wall. 

A wall or ceiling trap is eligible for detonation when a creature enters the 5 foot space directly in front of the sigil. If you move a trap, it cannot be activated until the start of your next turn and if it was moved under a creature.

At 15th level, you can move a sigil an additional 10 feet.

#### Mine Field
At 15th level, your expertise at maintaining your traps peaks, and you can now place and maintain two traps at once. When you place a third one while already maintaining two, you choose which of your existing two traps to destroy for it.

Both of these traps can be moved with Seamless Placement with the same bonus action, but they cannot exist in the same space as one another. Additionally, if you used your reaction to detonate a trap, you can detonate the second trap if it is able to be activated within the same round.

You can also now spawn a trap up to a location 10 feet away from you that you can see.

<div class='pageNumber'>27</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 3 | RANGER</div>
\page

### Skillshot Archer
The intuition of a hunter is the difference on getting the uppe hand on a target, or letting it give you the slip. However, even while predicting every move is impossible, there are plenty of options to adapt to these sudden changes. Skillshot Archers pride themselves on hitting the once in a million shots at a rather reliable rate. Many a Only a fool makes a bet with one of these rangers only to regret it soon after.

#### Finesse Archery
Some of your abilities from being a Skillshot Archer require creatures to make a saving throw. You use your Dexterity modifier when setting the saving throw DC for these features.

&nbsp;


**Feature save DC** = 8 + your proficiency bonus + your Dexterity modifier



#### Eagle’s Insight
At 3rd level, when using a shortbow or longbow as part of your Attack action, you can shoot an arrow straight up into the sky to land at an area within 60 feet of you on the start of your next turn as one of your attacks. Doing so requires you have 100 feet of open space above you. If a creature is in the arrows target area when it would land, that creature must succeed on a Dexterity saving throw or be struck by the arrow for double the amount of weapon die. If the creature being targeted did not see you when you loosed the arrow, they have disadvantage on their saving throw. This bonus damage increases to triple the amount of weapon die at 7th level.

#### Dead Shot
At 7th level, so long as you haven’t moved on your turn, you can spend your bonus action to drop your speed to 0 and focus your senses and mind on dealing a killing blow to your target. Your next attack roll against a creature has advantage and a critical hit range of 17-20. You can use this feature a number of times equal to your Wisdom modifier.

This cannot be used in conjunction with the Sharpshooter feature.

#### Dodge shot
At 11th level, twice during a round, whenever you are the target of a spell attack roll or ranged attack roll that misses you, you can use fire an arrow at your attacker as you spin away from their attack. The attacking creature must succeed on a Dexterity saving throw or be hit for (1d6+Half your Ranger level). You then can move 5 feet to an unoccupied space without provoking opportunity attacks and choose to be prone or not in your new location.

```
```

#### Mystical Barrage
At 15th level, As an action, you can shoot an arrow into the sky and spend a 4th level spell slot to multiply it into a barrage of arrows that blot out the sky. Target a location within 60 feet, and everything within a 15ft. radius of that spot is assaulted with your volley of arrows. All creatures within the area must succeed on a Dexterity saving throw or be hit for 4d10 piercing damage. On a successful save, they take half damage. If a creature in the area has less than 30 feet of movement speed, they have disadvantage on this saving throw. The conjured arrows that muddle the ground create magical difficult terrain until the start of your next turn when they disappear.

You can spend a 5th level spell slot to increase the damage of this attack by 2d10.

<div class='pageNumber'>28</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 4 | RANGER</div>
\page

## Rogue
With all the changes in the world, picking the right targets for rogues has been become more important. To aid their craft, some have delved further into the folds of magic that now floats around the world to aid their endeavors. While others simply decided to face these challenges head on by becoming more capable and strong. With folks like these lurking around, many a city treat even the simplest criminal as a dangerous threat to society. Too bad the ones they seem to catch are nothing but common pickpockets.

### Shadow Dagger
Your time of dabbling with magic to benefit your hobbies of mischief seems to have paid off. Whether from accidental encounters or excruciating study, you made contact with the Plane of Shadows successfully and it left you with a gift. Darkness now feels like a second home, and your movements are ignored. Those who cross you better watch their back, because you’re very likely to be right there before they realize it. 

#### Dark Refuge
Starting at 3rd level, you gain advantage on all Stealth checks made in dim light or darker. If you are invisible, you gain an extra die of Sneak Attack damage for any attacks made while being invisible.

#### Shadow Start
When you choose this Archetype at 3rd level, your arcane connection to the Plane of Shadows grants you respite. At the start of an encounter, after initiative is rolled but before the first turn is taken, you can choose to take a -10 penalty to your initiative to immediately become invisible until the end of your next turn. While you are invisible from this feature you have the Silenced condition and 5ft. of additional movement. 

You can use this feature once per long rest.

#### Hidden Point
At 9th level, you gain the ability to infuse your weapon of trade with your shadow magic. As an action, you can make a ranged attack roll with a dagger and once the attack is resolved, you turn invisible and teleport within 5 feet of where the dagger landed so long as it is within 30 feet. 

You can remain invisible from this feature until the end of your next turn, or until you make an attack, cast a spell, or take damage. You can use this feature 2 times, and all uses recharge with a long rest.

At 13th level, you gain an additional use of this feature.

```
```

#### Weaver of Shadows
At 13th level, your familiarity with the Plane of Shadows lets you manipulate shadows around you now. As a bonus action, you can touch a creature’s shadow with your hand that is not connected to any other creature’s shadow besides your own to raise it to aid you. The shadow reaches out from its plane, and attempts to ensnare its owner.

The targeted creature must succeed on a Strength saving throw with a saving DC equal to (10+proficiency bonus+Wisdom modifier). If the creature fails, it is restrained by its own shadow. The creature can attempt a new save at the end of each of its subsequent turns. On a successful save, the creature is not captured by the shadow and it returns to normal.

You can also use this feature to have your own shadow come to life and ensnare you to its surface as a reaction.

You can use this feature 2 times, and all uses recharge with a long rest.

#### Daggers of Darkness
At 17th level, You can materialize the energy from the Plane of Shadows to accompany your attack. If you use Sneak Attack on the same turn you are benefitting from Shadow Start or Hidden Point, you bring with you materialized shadow daggers to attack foes as you reappear. 8 shadow dagger that deals 1d4 Force damage appear around you and the target creature.

The shadow daggers can target any creature within 5ft. of you or your target. If the summoned daggers target the same creature you hit with Sneak attack, they automatically hit. If the daggers target a different creature, they have a bonus to their attack rolls equal to your proficiency bonus +2. You can use this feature once per long rest.

<div class='pageNumber'>29</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 1 | ROGUE</div>
\page

### Mage Hunter
Lots of spellcasters worry little about a normal person getting the drop on them. They become arrogant and reliant on their magic to save them and do the work for them. But you are here to remind them that they are nothing without their wands and incantations. When it comes down to it, the only thing their fancy words will do is paint a target on their backs for you. All there ever is to do is dance the dance til they’re cornered by you. That’s your favorite part.


#### Trained Mind
Starting at 3rd level, you gain a variety of benefits that have aided you against your magically inclined targets. You gain the following benefits:
* You have advantage on all Wisdom and Intelligence saving throws for spell effects.
* You gain a single use of Detect Magic that recharges on a long rest
* You gain proficiency in Arcana (Wis.) ability checks

#### Eye for Arcana
Also at 3rd level, as a bonus action, you can identify hostile creatures affinity for magic within 60 feet. Make an Arcana (Wis.) skill check with a DC equal to 14+1 per creature you want to test. On a  success, you know the maximum level spell slot the creatures have. If you fail your skill check, you learn nothing about any of the targeted creatures.

You can use this feature twice between long rests.

#### Bane of Mages
At 9th level, your familiarity with arcana has allowed you to redirect some of its impact away from you. Whenever you are targeted by a spell and damaged by fire, lightning, cold, thunder, poison, acid, or force damage, you can reduce the total damage taken by 1d4+1 per level spell slot of the spell cast.

Additionally, you ignore the effects of Mage Armor on creatures when making your attack rolls against them.

#### Magic Leech
At 13th level, When you succeed on a melee weapon attack roll against a creature that has spell slots, you can rob them of their spell slots to increase your damage or benefit yourself. As part of your successful attack roll, you can reach into their arcanic energy and use one of their second highest level spell slots (Minimum of 1st level) to cause 1 of 2 effects.
* Add unmitigatable magical damage to your attack equal to 1d8 per spell slot level stolen
* Create a magical shield for yourself, granting you immunity to Magic Missile and gain +1 AC per spell slot level of the stolen slot  until the start of your next turn.

You can use this feature a number of times equal to your Intelligence modifier (Minimum of 1). All uses of this feature recharge on a long rest.

```
```

#### New Trick
At 17th level, you have hunted so many magic users, and turned their own craft against them that some of the exposure has left you with an ability all your own. As an action, you can roll 1d4 and gain all of the effects equal to your rolled number and lower. (Ex. If you roll a 3, you gain the benefits of effects 1, 2, and 3.)
1. Become invisible as if casting the spell Invisibility and teleport 10 feet to any unoccupied location.
2. Leave an illusion of yourself in your current location as if using the spell Major Image. You decide what it is doing at the time of creation.
3. Gain a single use of Misty Step. If you already have Misty step, then your next usage of Misty Step within 1 hour gains 30 feet of range.
4. Your next successful attack roll against a creature that can cast spells disrupts them, forcing them to make a Constitution saving throw with a DC of (8+proficiency bonus+Intelligence modifier). On a fail they cannot cast spells, but can reattempt their saving throw at the end of each of their subsequent turns..

You can use this feature a number of times equal to your Intelligence modifier (Minimum of 1). All uses of this feature recharge on a long rest.

<div class='pageNumber'>30</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 2 | ROGUE</div>
\page

### Ruffian

Just because you travel with the crowd most people describe as rogues doesn’t mean you have to be a weak little pipsqueak. Ruffians revel in being skilled brawlers with and without a blade. They get through life by not trusting others and alway plotting on the best way and time to turn the tables on someone they are working with. You’ll typically find them at the local tavern, regaling their past glories while waiting for the right work to come their way so they can add to their list. They will work with who they have to for their own ends, and definitely have those they consider friends. But they owe their survival to their cautious nature, and are always looking for their next score.



#### Brutish Blow
Starting at 3rd level, you can add your Strength modifier to the damage roll of any successful Sneak Attack.

If a creature you hit with sneak attack is the same size or smaller than you, you can challenge them to a Strength contest. If you are victorious, you push them down with your attack and make them become prone. If they are victorious, you have disadvantage on attack rolls against them them until the end of your next turn.

#### Raised to Take a Hit
Also at 3rd level, your hit die for being a Rogue changes to 1d10. This increases your hit points maximum by 3 immediately. For all future Rogue levels, you now increase your maximum hit points by 1d10 (or 6) + your Constitution modifier.

You also gain proficiency in Strength saving throws.

#### Forceful hits
At 9th level, your unarmed strikes now hit for 1d4 + Strength modifier bludgeoning damage. On top of that, any attacks you perform without a Finesse or Ranged weapon can still activate your Sneak Attack , but with 1 less die than your normal Sneak Attack die amount. This however does not affect weapons with the Two-handed property.

#### Solo Fighter
At 13th level, If there is no other creature within 5 feet of you when you take the attack action, you can perform an additional attack as if you had Extra Attack. If you already have Extra Attack from a different source, you do not gain an additional attack.

```
```

#### Fiendish Throw
At 17th level, when you successfully hit a creature with Sneak attack, before calculating damage, you can challenge them to a Strength contest to try and hoist them up instead of just knocking them pron. If you are victorious in the contest and the creature is large or smaller, you hoist them into the air by the wound, causing you to automatically maximize half of your sneak Attack die used. You then can throw them up to 10 feet in any direction, causing an additional 1d6 bludgeoning damage from impact and to be knocked prone. If they collide with another Large or smaller creature, that additional creature must succeed on a Strength saving throw against your earlier Strength contest result or take the bludgeoning damage as well and be knocked prone. On a save, they take half damage and are not knocked prone. If the additional creature is Huge or larger, they will take no damage or be knocked prone.
If your original target creature is victorious in the contest, your attack damages them as normal but nothing further happens.

You can use this feature 2 times per long rest.

<div class='pageNumber'>31</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 3 | ROGUE</div>
\page

## Sorcerer
In an era of dragons, gods, and arcane forces, it is a miracle that anything but those things exists still at all. Yet, it is this very tenacity that has enabled the magic of the world to grow ever more powerful, and able to change to course of history. It is a heavy responsibility that sorcerers carry, as direct conduits of limitless magical forces. In every person touched by magic, they develop their own unique connection with it. Whether it be treading the thin line between life and death, or the natural elements that the inhabitants of this world mastered to rise above their primitive nature, Sorcerers are seekers of mastery to their power and potential. 

### Necromantic Sorcery
Necromancers get a rather distasteful reputation from the few bad apples who abuse their power. A normal necromancer finds respectable work in sacred places as a giver of closure to mourning families, or as investigators to mysterious murders for the city guard. But people tend to get the wrong idea when you treat a body as just a thing, which it is. The soul that inhabits a body is what is sacred; a fact you try to remind others of often. But alas, many have a hard time separating the two. But with this power, at least there are many possibilities available to your companionship.


#### Lost Essence
Starting at 1st level, you can try to capture any lingering life essence in a corpse that is less than 1 hour old into your spellcasting focus by spending 5 minutes sending them to the other side through a ritual of somatic and verbal rites but keeping some of their Essence they don’t need for yourself. The corpse must be intact and missing very little of its body. The creature must be at least medium in size, or be a Halfling, Dwarf, or Gnome. You cannot collect Essence from remains that have been reanimated once already.

You can store up to 3 Essences at 1st level. As a bonus action, you can access your stored Essences and spend as many as you have to gain one of the following benefits.
Gain 4 temporary hit points per Essence spent up to a maximum of 20. These temporary hit points last for 4 hours.
Heal 1d6+1 hit points per Essence spent
You can spend 2 essences to cast a Necromancy spell as 1 level higher than normal.
Select a number of creatures you can see equal to the number of Essences spent. Make a Stealth check against each creature against their Perception check. If the creature is unaware of you, you have advantage on this roll. If you succeed on your Stealth check, you are Invisible to that creature until the end of your turn.
You can convert 2 Essences to 1 Sorcerer point

You can store a total of 4 Essences at 14th level.

#### Necromancy Specialist
Also starting at 1st level, Animate Dead, Create Undead, Raise Dead, Resurrection, Revivify, Spare the Dying, Speak with Dead, Toll the Dead, True Resurrection, and Vampiric Touch become Sorcerer Spells for you. Whenever you successfully cast one of these spells, you also gain 1d4 hit points.

With this expertise, you can also identify the race of any remains by spending 1 minute examining them.

```
```

#### Bone Head
At 6th level, You gain resistance to Necrotic damage and can now turn skulls into a servant for a short time. As an action, you can touch a skull of a creature that has been dead for more than 1 year, to animate it. The animated skull has the stats listed below and rolls its own initiative.

The skull is friendly to you only and it obeys any verbal commands that you issue to it (no action required by you). If you don’t issue any commands to the skull, it defends itself from hostile creatures but otherwise takes no actions. A skull must be of a medium or smaller creature. The skull disintegrates to ash after 1 minute or is reduced to 0 hit points. You can only control 2 skulls at a time. If you choose to control a 3rd, the one with the lowest hit points disintegrates. If all active skull are at the same health, the one that was summoned first disintegrates.

___
> ## Animated Skull
>*Tiny Undead, Chaotic Neutral*
> ___
> - **Armor Class** 12 (Natural Armor)
> - **Hit Points** 22+Sorcerer Level (3d10+0)
> - **Speed** 0ft., 30ft. fly
>___
