### Elementalist

Shaped by the forces of nature, you have learned to bend them to your will by being in harmony with them in body and mind. Sorcerers with their origins in the elements often attribute their awakening to their powers through a landmark moment in their life where they first became one with their element. Often through a journey to find one's self or surviving a tremendously difficult trial versus nature.

#### Gaia Source
Your magical prowess comes from the world around you, all you do is shape it to your needs. Because of this, you do not excel at mastering many of the spells other spellcasters boast about, instead, you compete by witty combinations of your world shaping. Taking this Sorcerer Origin cuts your known spells by 3 with a minimum of 2 (This does not affect your known cantrips). You learn the spells listed in the Elemental Origin spells as you level up, and they count as Sorcerer spells for you and do not count towards the total number of spells known for you.

At 1st level, you choose two Cantrips and two first level spells to learn from the Elementalist spell list. You gain another cantrip and  1st level spell from the list at 3rd level, and the remaining cantrip and 1st level spell at 5th level. At 18th level, you learn the Overload spell from the Elementalist spell list


##### Elementalist Spells
| Sorcerer Level | Spells |
|:----:|:-------------|
| 1st  | Air Cannon, Combustion, Crag Dome, Earthen Pillar, Flaring Mote, Ice Shards, Sweeping Wave, Tornado Glide |
| 18th  | Overload |


#### Familiar Precision
At 6th level, your spells can be fused with your personal supply of arcane energy. When you cast a spell from the Elementalist spell list, you can spend 1 sorcery point to increase the total damage die used by 1. You can also spend 2 sorcery points to mimic this affect for a spell not on the Elementalist spell list.

<div class='pageNumber'>34</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 3 | SORCERER</div>
\page

#### Natural Fuel
At 14th level, you gain the ability to manipulate elements around you for your defense or spell slot replenishment. As an action, you can absorb a bit of natural energy from a source in the world within 30 feet to restore a spell slot equal to half your proficiency bonus. What counts as a source is listed below, as well as the alternative defensive option it offers.
The absorbing option can cost as many sorcery points as you see fit, while the defensive option only requires one. All defensive options are reactions and can be used after an attack against you is declared, but before the outcome is determined.

&nbsp;


**Air.** A non-magical wind that is strong enough to blow out a torch can be absorbed to replenish a spell slot. This can only be done once per short rest.

Alternatively, if you have the open sky above you, as a reaction you can spend a sorcery point to summon a downward gust of wind whenever you are the target of a ranged weapon attack to impose a -1d10 penalty on the attack roll.

&nbsp;


**Water.** A clean source of water that is at least 30 cubic feet in size can be absorbed to replenish a spell slot. This can only be done once per short rest.

Alternatively, when you are the target of a spell attack roll, if there is a source of water within 10ft. of you of at least 10 cubic feet in size, you can spend a sorcery point to pull forth a wave of the water and mix it with you magic to impose a -1d10 penalty on the attack roll.

&nbsp;


**Earth.** Ore or crystal of at least 10 cubic feet in size can be absorbed to replenish a spell slot. This can only be done once per short rest.

Alternatively, when you are the target of a melee attack, you can spend a sorcery point to pull earth directly beneath you up to you and give you +1d4 AC against the attack.

&nbsp;


**Fire.** A non-magical fire that is at least 10 cubic feet in size can be absorbed to replenish a spell slot. This can only be done once per short rest.

Alternatively, you can spend a sorcery point to flare up the fire to impose disadvantage on an incoming attack roll against a creature who can see the fire.

&nbsp;


Any combination of the defensive options can only be used a number of times equal to your Charisma modifier. All uses of this feature recharge on a long rest.

```
```

#### Elemental Fury

Starting at 18th level, you can change the casting of any spell from the Elementalist Spell List table into a bonus action casting time. Additionally, you can perform the following maneuvers at the cost of 3 sorcerer points.

&nbsp;


**Hurricane Winds.** You attempt to push, pull, or lift 2 creatures within 30 feet of you as an action. If the creature is unwilling, they must succeed on a Strength saving throw to avoid being moved. On a fail, they are moved up to 30 feet. If the creature collides with a solid surface they take 2d12 bludgeoning damage, if the solid surface is another creature, that creature must succeed on a Strength saving throw. On a fail, they take the same thunder damage as the moved creature. On a save, they take half damage.

&nbsp;


**Vitality Fountain.** You create a 10ft. cube of breathable water within 10 feet that has healing properties as an action. Any creature that ends its turn in the bubble heals 2d8 hit points at the start of their turn. Maintaining this cube requires concentration as if it were a spell. This cube lasts for 1 minute or until concentration ends.

&nbsp;


**Granite Thorns.** You create a 25 foot line of spiked earth wall that juts out at enemies as an action. This effect can only be activated if there is earth or stone along the line you choose. Make a ranged spell attack roll against any hostile creatures within 5 feet of the wall and on any successful attack, the creatures take 3d10 bludgeoning damage.

&nbsp;


**Slumbering Sparks.** You send forth a spark of flame as an action up to 30 feet away to a creature. The target must succeed on a Dexterity saving throw. On a fail, the sparks embeds itself into the creature, causing 2d8 fire damage immediately. On a save, they avoid the sparks and they float in midair until it is moved again as an action or after 1 minutes passes. As a bonus action, if the spark is within 60 feet and embedded into a creature, you can detonate it and cause an explosion in a 10 foot radius of it. All creatures within this range must succeed on a Dexterity saving throw, but the creature embedded with the sparks automatically fails. On a fail, a creature takes 3d8 fire damage, and half damage on a save. The sparks provide bright light in a 10ft. radius and dim light for an additional 10ft.

&nbsp;


You can use these features a number of times equal to your Wisdom modifier (Minimum of 1). All uses of this feature recharge on a long rest.

<div class='pageNumber'>35</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 4 | SORCERER</div>
\page


### False-Mind
When one steps back and looks at the world, they realize that it is different and unique to everyone. No two people see the same flower, or hear the same cry. Understanding this, it turns out, is the key to a convincing illusion. By reading the flow of life around all living things, Sorcerers of the False-Mind can cater an illusion to their recipients preferences. They can show things that shouldn’t be possible, and even fool other senses. After all, it isn’t the eyes you have to fool, but the mind behind them.

#### Trick of the Eye
Starting at 1st level, whenever you cast an illusion spell and a creature is affected by it or targets it for inspections, that creature suffers a -2 to Investigation checks against the illusions, and a -1 to saving throws to break through an illusion. Additionally, if an illusion is seen through or interacted with, you can choose for it to cause 1d6 psychic damage on the interacting or investigating creature so long as you can see the moment it is interacted with or seen through. This does not affect the spell Mirror Image.

At 14th level, this effect increases to a -3 to Investigation checks against the illusions, a -2 to saving throws, and the illusions can cause 2d6 psychic damage when they are interacted with or investigated. At 18th level, the damage increases to 3d8 psychic damage.

#### A Touch of Realism
Also starting at 1st level, choose one 1st level illusion spell to know in addition to your normal number of known spells from any spell list. Even if it isn’t from the Sorcerer spell list, it counts as a sorcerer spell for you. You can also use 2 Sorcerer Points to add a single attribute of smell, sound, or temperature to an illusion that normally would not have it as part of the casting.

At 6th level, you can spend 2 sorcery points to impose disadvantage on a creatures Investigation or Perception check against an illusion spell you cast so long as you can see them.

#### Honed Mind
At 6th level, you are fully trained in the way of the mind, granting you the following bonuses.
* You have advantage to saving throws against being Charmed
* You have immunity from Fear from magical sources
* You have advantages on skill checks and saving throws against Illusion spells.
* If you take psychic damage, you can choose to spend sorcery points to reduce the damage by 2d6 per point spent.

```
```
#### Inception
At 14th level, you can try and convince a target that it wants to do something contrary to its current course of action. As an action, you can speak to a creature and suggest to it another course of action in 10 words or less. To do so successfully, a Creature must fail on a Wisdom saving throw against your spell save DC, and additionally, you must succeed on a Deception check against the creatures passive Insight (10+Insight). The creature must be able to hear you, share a same language as you, and have at least an Intelligence of 4. The creature will not listen to obviously detrimental suggestions such as harming itself or an ally. If this feature is successful, the creature does not know you influenced it ever, and believes its actions or train of thought was its own idea.

#### Mass Mirror Image
At 18th level, as an action you can provide yourself and up to 3 allies within 60 feet with duplicates from the spell Mirror Image. Choose from yourself and your chosen allies for one of you to receive 3 duplicates, another receive 2 duplicates, and the last 2 chosen receive 1 duplicate. You can use this ability once per long rest.

<div class='pageNumber'>36</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 1 | SORCERER</div>
\page

## Warlock
With the reshaping of the world, entities from beyond the planes have come forth to stake their claim. These entities act as Patrons to those able to reach out to them, and are willing to accept new power in exchange for their service. What these forces want is not always understood, but they are sure to let their wards know when they are stepping out of line. What these beings are capable of is unknown, but based on the abilities of their charges, they should be watched with full attention.

### The Nameless

You have made a pact with an entity stripped of form, and name. Only raw emotion and willpower remain, and you are its new instrument of influence. This entity desires that a ruthless justice and truth of the world be followed through against transgressors to promises or secretes. To this end, it will allow you to touch the hearts of others to bring to the surface the secrets they keep to hide their true selves from the world. Knowledge is sacred, and those who would hide it are the scum of the land.

#### Expanded Spell List
The Nameless lets you choose from an expanded list of spells when you learn a warlock spell. The following spells are added to the warlock spell list for you.

##### The Nameless Expanded Spells
| Paladin Level | Spells |
|:----:|:-------------|
| 1st  | Dissonant Whispers, Wrathful Smite |
| 2nd  | Darkness, Zone of Truth |
| 3rd  | Bestow Curse, Remove Curse |
| 4th  | Blight, Phantasmal Killer |
| 5th  | Hold Monster, Destructive Wave |



#### The Words of the World
At 1st level, Your Patron shares with you the secrets of truths and lies that mortals tell. You gain advantage on all Insight, and Deception skill checks. You also have the ability to lie while under the influence of Zone of Truth without alerting the caster to the fact that you are lying. You can do this by succeeding on a Wisdom saving throw against their spell save DC

#### Blood Oath
At 6th level, you learn the secrets of empathy and infuse your magic with it. As a reaction, you can swear a Blood Oath of Vengeance against the creature that last damaged you. A creature you have Blood Oathed is now linked to you. Until you or that creature drops to 0 hit points, or 1 minute passes, that creature takes 1d6 Psychic damage for every 5 points of health you lose from the moment of swearing the Oath up to a maximum of 5 times your Warlock level. You can only have 1 creature be targeted with this feature at a time. A creature can only have a Blood Oath sworn on it once every hour.

```
```

#### Secrets Revealed
At 10th level, you hear whispers from the Ethereal Plane on the battlefield about your foes; whispers of their weaknesses. As a bonus action, you can focus your attention on the whispers and gain advantage on attack rolls against a foe of your choice that you can see for 1 hour. This creature also suffers disadvantage to saving throws from spells cast by you. This feature can be used once per long rest

#### Loss of Identity
At 14th level, your Patron seeks to have others suffer its own demise. As an action, you can banish a non-undead foe as if casting the spell Banishment and send them to your Patron. Your target is torn apart at the mind as your Patron forces them to live the travesties and injustices of countless lives. Your target takes 1d4+1 psychic damage per Warlock level. At the end of your next turn, the target returns to the space it previously occupied, or the nearest unoccupied space. Should the creature die during this experience, their body is not returned and you instead receive temporary hit points equal to your Warlock level. Once you use this feature, you can’t use it again until you finish a long rest. A creature subjected to this experience can never undergo it again.

<div class='pageNumber'>37</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 1 | WARLOCK</div>
\page


### The Great Dragon

You have made a pact with one responsible for the lives of all of Dragon-kind. Entities responsible for the oversight of Dragons and their kin are Io, Aasterinian, Astilabor, Bahamut, Chronepsis, Faluzure, Garyx, Hlal, Lendys, Sardior, Tamara, and Tiamat. Regardless of your origin, you have piqued their interest when you contacted them and they have decided to grant you some of their power to see how things unfold. Through your tenacity and determination you now walk among society with the power of Dragon blood flowing through your veins, and an ability with the arcane to match.

#### Expanded Spell List
The Great Dragon lets you choose from an expanded list of spells when you learn a warlock spell. The following spells are added to the warlock spell list for you.

##### The Great Dragon Expanded Spells
| Paladin Level | Spells |
|:----:|:-------------|
| 1st  | Chromatic Orb, Disguise Self |
| 2nd  | Darkvision, Magic Mouth |
| 3rd  | Fireball, Protection from Energy |
| 4th  | Conjure Minor Elemental, Polymorph |
| 5th  | Conjure Elemental, Legend Lore |


#### Draconic Heritage
At 1st level, Your Patron shares with you the secrets or harnessing Dragon’s Breath. You have ties to Dragonborn powers as if you had draconic ancestry. Choose one type of dragon from the Draconic Ancestry table. Breath weapon and damage resistance are determined by the dragon type, as shown in the table.
	
##### Draconic Ancestry
| Dragon | Damage Type | Breath Weapon |
|:------:|:------------|:--------------|
| Black  | Acid | 5 by 30 ft. line (Dex. Save) |
| Blue  | Lightning | 5 by 30 ft. line (Dex. Save) |
| Brass  | Fire | 5 by 30 ft. line (Dex. Save) |
| Bronze  | Lightning | 5 by 30 ft. line (Dex. Save) |
| Copper  | Acid | 5 by 30 ft. line (Dex. Save) |
| Gold  | Fire | 15 ft. cone (Dex. save) |
| Green  | Poison | 15 ft. cone (Dex. save) |
| Red  | Fire | 15 ft. cone (Dex. save) |
| Silver  | Cold | 15 ft. cone (Dex. save) |
| White  | Cold | 15 ft. cone (Dex. save) |

```
```

#### Breath Weapon    
You can use your action to exhale destructive energy. Your draconic ancestry determines the size, shape, and damage type of the exhalation. When you use your breath weapon, each creature in the area of the exhalation must make a saving throw, the type of which is determined by your draconic ancestry. The DC for this saving throw equals 8 + your Constitution modifier + your proficiency bonus. A creature takes 2d6 damage on a failed save, and half as much damage on a successful one. The damage increases to 3d6 at 6th level, 4d6 at 11th level, and 5d6 at 16th level. After you use your breath weapon, you can’t use it again until you complete a short or long rest.

If you already have Draconic Ancestry from another source, you may choose a second Dragon type to benefit from, and can use both types for your breath weapon as you see fit. This also doubles how often you can use your breath weapon.

Lastly, you also can speak, read, and write Draconic.


#### Traits of the Drake
At 6th level, you are now comfortable enough with the draconic magic within you that you are constantly channeling it and some new side effects manifest as a result. You gain the following benefits.

* You grow patches of scales that cover your body now. Your AC without armor becomes 13+Dex. Modifier. At 10th level, you gain more scales and your AC increases to 14+Dex.
* Your Eldritch Blasts now deal 1d4 additional damage of the element based on your Draconic Heritage chosen for this subclass. This increases to 1d6 at 10th level.
* Resistance to the damage type of your draconic ancestry.

#### Born Within
At 10th level, you gain the ability to sprout wings at will for 5 minutes each day. These wings grant you a fly speed of 20 ft.

Additionally, your Evocations that affect your Eldritch Blast can now be used with your Breath Weapon with the exception of Eldritch Spear.

<div class='pageNumber'>38</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 2 | WARLOCK</div>
\page

#### Herald of the Dragon
At 14th level, You can open a flaming 10 by 10 foot portal on the ground next to you, to summon forth the lurching head of a dragon, gifted to you in aid by your Patron. The dragon resembles the same type as you chose from Draconic Heritage. The Dragon’s stats are as stated below and has its own initiative order, but it is immovable from its summoned location. At the time of being summoned, the dragon occupies a 10 foot cube area, but can extend its neck another 10 feet from the portal. You can communicate with the dragon in Draconic, and it will listen to your orders and requests so long as it is not self-harming.

Your breath weapon is empowered while you are within 5 feet of the Dragon’s head, increasing its power by 3d6 and increasing its ange by 10 feet.

___
