### The Vessel of the Lost

You have made a pact with the lost souls of the Void between planes to be their vessel. They scream out to you and beckon you to give them life, if only for just a while. You are able to reach out to them by making a deal with their protector and watcher, who in exchange for servicing his subjects with an answer to their cries, you may borrow their strengths and powers. With this, you become a jack of all trades, continuously warping your own mind by melding it with others, but inheriting their skill sets in the process.

#### Expanded Spell List
The Lost lets you choose from an expanded list of spells when you learn a warlock spell. The following spells are added to the warlock spell list for you.

##### The Vessel of the Lost Expanded Spells
| Paladin Level | Spells |
|:----:|:-------------|
| 1st  | Blade Ward, False Life |
| 2nd  | Calm Emotions, Mind Spike |
| 3rd  | Protection from Energy, Spirit Guardians |
| 4th  | Locate Creature, Phantasmal Killer |
| 5th  | Dominate Person, Raise Dead |


#### Harbored Soul
At 1st level, You now become a vessel to harbor a soul from beyond the Material Plane. Who you channel is sometimes hard to control, but regardless of who it is, it is always brief, so not too dangerous. As an action, roll 1d6 to determine whether you have control on what soul you select.

The soul that inhabits you acts at half of your current Warlock level (Minimum of 1) for the purposes of the strength of their abilities you gain.

When you harbor a soul, you gain temporary hit points equal to their Hit Die as their vitality fills you. Additionally, you learn the race of the soul you are harboring, and learn 1 language that they know if they know an additional language you don’t know already (DM’s discretion).
  
If a soul lets you learn a spell, you can only learn spells that would be available to that class at the stated level. All knowledge, ability, and proficiency of the gained abilities leave you along with the summoned soul after 1 hour or once you dismiss the soul as an action.

You can only harbor 1 soul at a time, and trying to harbor a new soul fails to yield results. The soul also leaves you if you become unconscious. Sometimes a bit of the souls personality may fuse into yours during the joined time together,but that is up to the DM’s discretion. You can use this feature a number of times equal to the number of Warlock Spell Slots you have.

| 1d6 | Result |
|:----:|:-------------:|
| 1-2  | Randomly select what Class the soul you harbor is from the table below by rolling 1d12 |
| 3-6  | Choose which soul to harbor based on Class |

```
```

#### Harbored Soul Selection
| 1d12 | Class | Hit Die | Gained Abilities from Harbored Soul|
|:----:|:-----:|:-------:|:----------------------------------:|
| 1 | Barbarian | d12 |  Rage class feature, Proficiency in martial weapons and Constitution saving throws, +2 bonus to your Strength score (To a maximum of 20) |
| 2 | Bard | d8 |  Bardic Inspiration class feature, Proficiency in 1 instrument and the Performance Skill, +2 bonus to your Charisma score (To a maximum of 20) |
| 3 | Cleric | d8 |  1 use of the spell Cure Wounds without it consuming a spell slot, Proficiency in the Religion Skill, +2 bonus to your Wisdom score (To a maximum of 20)|
| 4 | Druid | d8 |  Wild Shape class feature, Proficiency in Animal Handling, +2 bonus to your Wisdom score (To a maximum of 20)|
| 5 | Fighter | d10 |  Second Wind class feature, Proficiency in martial weapons and all armor, +2 bonus to your Strength score (To a maximum of 20)|
| 6 | Monk | d8 |  Martial Arts class feature, 5 feet additional movement Speed, +2 bonus to your Dexterity score (To a maximum of 20)|
| 7 | Paladin | d10 |  Lay on Hands class feature: Your pool equals your Warlock level +7, Proficiency in Medicine and Religion, +2 bonus to your Wisdom score (To a maximum of 20)|
| 8 | Ranger | d10 |  Natural Explorer class feature, Proficiency in Nature and Survival, +2 bonus to your Dexterity score (To a maximum of 20)|
| 9 | Rogue | d6 |  Sneak Attack class feature, Proficiency in Stealth, +2 bonus to your Dexterity score (To a maximum of 20)|
| 10 | Sorcerer | d6 |  Choose a 1st level spell from the Sorcerer spell list to learn, Proficiency in Charisma and Constitution saving throws, +2 bonus to your Charisma score (To a maximum of 20)|
| 11 | Warlock | d8 |  You gain an additional spell slot of your current available Slot Level, Double your proficiency bonus for Wisdom and Charisma saving throws, +2 bonus to your Charisma score (To a maximum of 20)|
| 12 | Wizard | d6 |  You gain 1 Spell Slot and 1 spell from the Wizard spell list to learn that are 1 level lower than your current maximum Spell Slot Level, Proficiency in Intelligence saving throws, +2 bonus to your Intelligence score (To a maximum of 20)|

<div class='pageNumber'>40</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 4 | WARLOCK</div>
\page



#### Phantom Assist
At 6th level, you can set loose your Harbored soul into an enemy within 5 feet that has an Intelligence of at least 4, as an action. The creature must succeed on a Wisdom saving throw or have the soul move into them. Because they are not accustomed to harboring an additional soul, they will have to roll on the Phantom Assist Table below and have that effect happen immediately. If the Creature succeeds on their saving throw, the soul will rejoin with you at the start of your next turn.

#### Phantom Assist Table
| 1d4 | Result |
|:----:|:-------------|
| 1 | The creature becomes feared by all other creatures. It remains feared until it succeeds on a subsequent saving throw at the end of its turns. |
| 2 | The creature disarms itself and cannot use bonus actions or reactions until the start of your next turn. The soul then leaves. |
| 3 | The creature takes 2d6 psychic damage but then expels the spirit. This increases to 2d8 psychic damage at 14th level. |
| 4 | The creature is able to push out the soul, forcing it to leave, but has disadvantage on its next attack roll while they recover from the experience. |


While a creature has the harbored soul within it, you do not benefit from their bonuses, but neither does the creature they inhabit. You can recall the soul back to you as an action if the creature is within 5 feet of you and the soul hasn’t left yet.

#### Stronger souls
At 10th level, the bonus to ability scores granted by souls increases to +3 (to a maximum of 20).

Additionally, whenever you have to roll a d12 for Harbored Soul, you may roll 2d12's and use either result.

```
```

#### Possession
At 14th level, your Patron teaches you the secret of moving souls yourself, allowing you to move yours to invade another's.

As an action, you attempt to invade a creature through a Charisma contest between you and a creature within 10 feet you can see that has less than your amount of current hit points.

If the creature has taken the Attack action in the last 5 minutes, you have disadvantage on this contest roll. If the creature is Frightened, Grappled, Restrained, or Stunned, you gain a +1 bonus to your contest roll. If the creature is Incapacitated, Petrified, or Unconscious, they are immune to this ability and cannot be targeted for a soul transfer.

If you attempt to possess a creature, but their hit points are more than your current hit points or you lose the contest, the possession is unsuccessful and unavailable for 24 hours.

If you succeed in sending your soul to the creature, you gain their stat block and current health points and can remain within their body for 5 minutes. You take their place in initiative during this time. You do not gain any of their memories, or learn any of their languages, features, or spells if you do not already know them yourself. If they do not have spell slots, you cannot use any of your spellcasting abilities.

While you are possessing a body, your own goes limp and is unconscious. If you are reduced to 0 hit points in the body you are occupying, your soul returns to your original body so long as it is on the same plane of existence and not dead. upon such time, you immediately take any leftover damage beyond what reduced your possessed body to 0 as psychic damage. If your original body is reduced to 0 hit points, or 5 minutes passes, you are pulled back into it immediately so long as you are on the same plane of existence as it. If you are not on the same plane of existence when you are pulled back to your body, your soul lingers in place where your body last was until your body returns to the same plane of existence.

You must succeed on another Charisma contest at the end of each of your turns using the body in order to keep possessing it. On a fail, you are forced out by the host and take 1d8 psychic damage per turn you occupied it.

<div class='pageNumber'>41</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 5 | WARLOCK</div>
\page
## Wizard
With so much changing in the world, the knowledge to be sought seems truly infinite. But one can strive for the impossible, and will witness many a miracle along the way. The ultimate seekers of knowledge who delve themselves into the study and practice of magic are capable of wonderous creations and abilities. Yet they remain unsatisfied, as they know that there will always be more to learn and create.


### School of Animation
Your studies as a transmutation mage has brought your attention to the fact that objects can be manipulated to imitate life. Usually this discovery starts out with a simple curiosity if an assistant can be made to help with arcane pursuits, while others see a means of protection. After a while, some of these desires and wonders can expand to questionable morals or building an army of constructs, or a single, all powerful golem.

### Transmutation Savant
Starting at 2nd level, the gold and time you must spend to copy a transmutation spell into your spellbook is halved. You gain proficiency in Smith’s Tools, Carpenter’s Tool’s and Mason’s Tools.

### Personal Touch
Starting at 2nd level when you choose this school, you add the Find Familiar spell to your spellbook if you do not already have it, and can cast it without the normal material cost. When you cast the spell, you can choose to sacrifice 2 pounds worth of material to create the familiar as a Construct with certain extra properties depending on what material was used

#### Construct Properties
| Material | Property |
|----------|----------|
|Fiber|Has a fly speed of 10 feet|
|Stone|Gains an additional 2d8 maximum hit points|
|Metal|Gains +2 to AC|
|Crystal/Gem|Can cast 2nd level magic missile once per long rest|

```
```

#### Selfmade Soldiers
Starting at 6th level, As an action, you can use a 2nd level spell slot to animate a non-magical weapon or non-magical armor that is not being worn or carried that you touch. A weapon has the statistics of a Flying Sword, and a piece of armor has the statistics of an Animated Armor.

The weapon or armor becomes a creature under your control for 1 hour or until the creature is reduced to 0 hit points. At the start or end of the creatures turn , if it is more than 30 feet from you, it returns to being a non-magical item and can’t be reanimated for 1 hour.

As a bonus action, you can mentally control your animation. You decide what action the creature will take and where it will move during its next turn, or you can issue a general command, such as to guard a particular room. If you issue no commands, the creature only defends itself against hostile creatures. Once given an order, the construct continues to follow it until its task is complete or the animation wears off.

An animated weapon or armor becomes brittle and unusable after the animation effect has ended, becoming broken equipment

At 10th level, you can also cast transmutation spells from these constructs if they are within 30 feet.

#### Focused Animation
Beginning at 10th level, you can now infuse a familiar summoned with Find Familiar with 2 materials to grant it extra properties. Additionaly you can now cast transmutation spells from your familiar without it having a range of touch. 

<div class='pageNumber'>42</div>
<div class='footnote'>PART 1 | Wizard</div>
\page

#### True Construct
Starting at 14th level you learn the spell Stone Shape if you do not already know it, but you can now use it to also affect wood and metal, and crystals/gems for the purposes of this feature. Whenever you touch at least 10 cubic feet worth of metal, crystal/gems ,wood, or stone, you can cast Stone Shape and spend 1 hour to morph it into a True Construct. True constructs have the following properties:
* They do not need concentration to be maintained
* They remain alive until they break or are reduced to 0 hit points.
* They use our Spell save DC for their features.

You can mentally command a True Construct you create if it is within 100 feet of you. A true construct will follow your instructions to the best of its ability. You might command the construct to accompany you on an adventure, to guard a location, deliver a package, etc. When a true construct has completed its instructions, it will travel to you if you are on the same plane of existence. If you are on a different plane of existence, it returns to the place it was last instructed to stay or where it was animated until you return.

You can only have one Construct under your command at a time. If you try to create another while you have one, it will not come to life. True Constructs have their own initiative separate from you in encounters. They do not need to eat or sleep, and cannot communicate to you physically or mentally, though it understands you perfectly. 

True Constructs cannot be healed by means other than being worked on by their relevant tool kit. With 1 pounds worth of material, you can heal a Metal construct with Smith’s Tools,  A Crystal/Gem construct with Jeweler’s Tools, a Wooden construct with Carpenter’s Tools, and a Stone construct with Mason’s Tools.

The amount of healing is equal to the number rolled for the relevant tool kit set skill check made with the tools. It takes one hour to make the repairs to your True Construct.

True constructs are not immune to the ravages of time and thus decay at the rate of the objects they are made of. As the constructs condition worsens, its maximum hit points decrease. If the construct reaches 0 hit points, the effect ends and the now lifeless material is no longer eligible to be used to make a new True Construct. Metal decays 1d12 health per year. Crystal/Gem decays at 2d6 per month, Stone decays 1d12 health per month. And wood decays 1d12 health every week. You can create a True construct once every 7 days.

___
> ## True Construct (Wood)
>*Medium Construct, Unaligned*
